comments: At Corpus Christi's Hans and Pat Suter Refuge, found five monarch caterpillars, ranging from 2 to 5 cm long, on 1/02/00.  Also found one new milkweed butterfly chrysalis, but seemed small; may be queen.  Had seen one 3 cm monarch caterpillar on 12/26/00.  Adults of queen & monarchs had been visiting the Mexican milkweed all through December 1999, and one monarch was seen emerging from its chrysalis on 12/13/99.Weather has been maxing in mid-70s to low 80s past two weeks, with no precip.  Winds gusting to 30 knots from SE on 1/02, so not surprised to see no monarchs, but did see 1 queen.  Is this part of a Texas overwintering monarch population?

In Harris County, southwest Houston, I have had monarch butterflies off and on all winter. I have collected eggs all winter and raised the larvae. In the last 10 days I released 4 butterlies and currently have 4 in chrysalis in a rearing cage outside. I cannot keep enough milkweed as all have been eaten - a lot of cuttings have been started but are not mature enough to put in the ground. I planted milkweed in my neighbors yard and he has many eggs on his 2 plants.

We have had such a mild winter here, that the milkweeds havecontinued blooming all winter.  I have had a number of monarchbutterflies hatch from their chrysalis throughout December andJan 2000.  I did find a few that did not survive a cold snapin late December.  The chrysalis was translucent with dark interior, but obviously "dead" as it was somewhat shriveled and hard.I brought in several large larva (1 to 1.5") to pupate indoors as I was concerned about the weather.  When I released the new butterflies to the backyard, they took several hours to fly off.

Milam Elementary School (about 10 miles from the Mexico border), Mrs Merritt's 4th grade class was maintaining the butterfly garden when second and third stage larva were found on the milkweed plants.  Also, some eggs were found and two days later first stage larva were found.  We have not sighted the butterflies that laid these eggs but are looking for them!

We have had a few monarchs all winter in Victoria.  We began to find several eggs and larvae at school the second week of February.  After our cold snap in late January, the students began a few larvae.  One student looked for and found about 80 eggs during the second and third weeks of February on the A. curassavica at school.  We have not released any raised monarchs since late October ...  so all that we have seen have grown up in the area on backyard tropical milkweed ... unless there is some milkweed (tropical or native) that survived on the barrier islands or right along the bays ... and that question remains to be answered.

We have 6 small tropical milkweek plants in our butterfly garden that was planted last fall at school.  Every day for the past week, students have been finding larva and eggs.  As of today 12 larva have been found.  The students stopped counting at 20 eggs.  We have yet to see an adult Monarch.  Our school is on the border of Texas and Mexico - we are wondering if a few Monarchs are starting northward!

Approximately 15 monarch larvae from 1 to 2 inches in lengthwere found on one 15 inch high milkweed plant in my backyard on March 11,2000. I redistributed them to other plants, and they are happily munching away.  From across the yard I noticed that theplant had lost all its leaves and flowers, while all the othermilkweeds in the garden were in full flower. On close inspection, I saw that the entire plant was covered with Monarchlarvae!

Two Monarchs visited 3 days ago, and fought over rights to lay eggs on my very tired milkweed plants that wintered over.  I counted 10 eggs being layed at that time.  To my surprise, today, I checked on the eggs, and discovered 2 larvae eating away.  I haven't learned how to guess "enstars" yet, but past experience tells me these guys hatched about 3-4 days ago since they are relatively small.  I will have to hurry to purchase more milkweed, and to make sure the wasps don't get the young caterpillars.

We found the first 5th instar monarch larvae on the wild Asclepias viridis 5.5 miles east-southeast of Victoria this afternoon.  We had been finding 1st thru 4th over the weekend near Port Lavaca ...  evidence of larval activity, but we seldom find any larvae.  We have also been noticing large fire ant nests in the area!  The largest of the seed pods on the A.v. plants in this patch measured 92 mm in length today.  We have been observing these plants since February 15.

I was in Mexico touring the monarch reserves week before last with a group lead by Bill Calvert. At a resort near the Agua Blanca springs I found 2nd instar larvae and eggs on _Asclepias curassavica_.

I found 8-12 no. of 0-1 instar larva on a Asclepias incarnata 'Ice Ballet', which I left in it's pot to go dormant in the garden in the spot where I wish to plant it out.  After seeing the  handsome Monarch in the garden the other day, I thought I'd better do a close inspection of my milkweeds, and low and behold, there they are, less than an 3/16" in length.  This after a tremendous storm about 4.0 a.m. this morning! Brought the pot up to the house, to better photograph it, and to offer some protection, until I can put a net sleeve over it. The plant is in a one gallon pot and is only just starting to shoot up. The weather remained rainy to partly sunny, and a cool front moved in after lunch today, and those little guys have stopped moving around.  Can't wait to see them in the morning!. Photos on request, jpg or other....send saemail.  State your sizerequirement.  I hope to have them up on a web page in the next couple of weeks, so stay tuned.
I found my first larvae of the year. Two were on a small sprig of _Asclepias curassavica_ this afternoon. I hope the plant grows fast enough to keep them fed.
Six fat caterpillars have devoured the milkweed and 5 made it to chrysalis. The sixth was attacked (by wasps) I think.

I noticed a fairly large monarch caterpillar on a texas milkweed (Asclepias texana) plant in my garden at 8:30 am.   The plant had all of its leaves.  I also noticed a mexican milkweed (Asclepias curassavica) nearby that was completely defoliated.   The caterpillar must have moved over to the Texas milkweed after eating the other.  I had been away just for a few days so I missed seeing the eggs & young larva.   This evening there was one more monarch larva eating away on the texas milkweed!
We have 4 small caterpillars and there's a couple dozen eggs on the Asclepias.
First Monarch Larva spotted this morning on a. incarnata plant.

We located our first monarch larva at mr. Barton's home and at school ( North Hall Middle ) we were very excited and intrigued to discover it. we students are very pleased to Have observed such a wonderfull discovery.

Our first two Monarch eggs hatched today. The larva ate their egg cases then moved on to eating their Syriaca leaf.  These eggs were laid one week ago on Wed. Apr 19.  Yesterday we noticed the eggs turning dark especially at the tip where they were black.

I was so excited that I wanted to send out birth announcements when I discovered 11 tiny monarch caterpillers on one of the milkweed plants in the Parkville Nature Sanctuary.  They are the size of a pencil lead - so tiny!  They have eaten holes the size of pencil erasers in the leaves.  It is plant #10, the one in the chatted road bed.  I was right, there were eggs on it seven days ago on 4/28.  I have found no other eggs or larva on any of the other plants. The adult monarch chose the sturdiest of the plants for her egg laying.  I look forward to monitoring the tiny critters through adulthood.

I searched about 40 Common Milkweed plants at Pine Spur Overlook on the Blue Ridge Parkway and found 16 Monarch Caterpillars ranging from very tiny to about "half grown".  A species of earwig was also eating the very newest leaves and some flower buds that were just beginning to form.

Every spring we order monarch larvae from the Univ. of Kansas MonarchWatch program.  We collect milkweed from our area to feed them.  Today when we were feeding them we noticed a tiny, tiny one on the leaf.  Apparently before we collected this bunch an adult monarch had laid an egg which hatched in our classroon unbeknowst to us!  It was exciting as all but one of our caterpillars had gone into chrysalis and the students were sad to "see them go"  now we can enjoy one a bit longer!!
When I was in South Florida visiting my granddaughter, I saw a monarch in her backyard as well as a monarch caterpillar on a milkweed plant.  (Plantation is near Ft. Lauderdale.)

Sighted two faded adult monarchs in town on Wednesday.  There have been many eggs this week on the new growth on the A. curassavica (checking now for monarch or queen).  Overwintering groups of adult monarchs (twenty to over one hundred) observed since Christmas in Matagorda, Calhoun, and Aransas Counties near the bays.  Asclepias viridis, A. asperula, and A. tuberosa just breaking thru the surface.  Backyard A. curassavica never lost all their leaves and after cutting back already have flower buds.  Monarch and a few queen larvae all winter.  Should be past last frost.  Corn planting started on Wednesday.
I saw a rather large (5th instar?) caterpillar chewing on the (just-emerging-after-the-first-freeze in years-back-in-Jan) baby milkweed leaves.  I'll keep checking and let you know
I just saw a larva chewing milkweedAnd I   think it was the egg I reported before.
school: St. john greek orthodox day school

comments: Found two larva on our milkweed.  Our Milkweed has been blooming all winter, but this is the first larva found since the fall.  Unusually cold winter.

A student, Hayden McGhee found two monarch larva, 2nd stage on milkweed at his home in McAllen.  This is the first larva seen since fall at his home.  This makes a total of four found in our area in a week.

John and Lus Maria Hagey live in Harlingen, Cameron Co., the southmostcounty in Texas. I talked to John and he said that he observed a femaleMonarch laying eggs for about 45 minutes on either the 13th or 14th ofFebruary. He said that all these larvae appear to be the same age and thathe first noticed they were devouring the tropical milkweed on March 6th.Their milkweed is planted on the north side of their house. The firstMonarch they noticed was on January 6th.Mike Quinn, TPWD

Greetings from Miami.  Our Butterfly Garden was full of Monarch caterpillars on March 16,2001.  They have been eating steadly and growing.  Almost all of our milkweed has been devoured and only the stems remain.  We counted at least 15 on some of the branches.  As reported before a member of our thrid generation seemed to flutter around the garden.  It is exciting watching the fourth generation.
Do their eggs overwinter? Our milkweed is full of larvae, some of which are pupating already. (Reported for Greg Pye by Mike Quinn, Texas Parks and Wildlife.)
Found five eggs south of Austin around the San Marcos area.  The milkweed is abundant and healthy.
I found the first larva while working in the garden. There havebeen a couple of monarchs but so far there have not been any larvae.  It was probably in the second instar.

We checked a ten yard by ten yard square of Asclepias viridis that is now blooming in Victoria and on thirty stems found four first instar monarch larvae, one second instar, three latex mustaches, but no eggs.  These are the first monarch larvae we have found on native, wild milkweed in the area.  We have found latex mustaches before indicating small larvae ... no larvae, but always many fire ants in those cases!  Netted, photo'd, tagged, and released a faded and tattered female working another patch of A. viridis in the area ... compared with a "new" female at: http://apr2k1.homestead.com/apr6.html

we found today about 50 monarch cats on our newly emerging scarlet milkweed. most all of them are about 1 inch long. there is no way there is enough food to  get all of them to their final instar. we were suprised to find them because we have not seen any adults except one that came through in a hurry last week.

At Brazos Bend State Park about 1 hour south of Houston, a naturalist and I saw Swamp Milkweed in Creekfield Lake last Saturday.  The Milkweed is blooming, and we found 4 small larvae on the plants, they were monarch larvae. One larvae was about1/2 inch long, the others were about 1/8 inch.

Last Friday in Brazos Bend State Park about 1 hour south ofHouston, a park naturalist and I saw 4 monarch larvae onSwamp Milkweed next to Creekfield Lake.  The milkweed is inbloom.  The larvae were tiny, from about 1/8 inch to 1/2 inch insize.  Interestingly, the Mexican Milkweed nearby that isplanted in a garden at the Observatory near where we found the swamp milkweed has no eggs or larvae.  Do they prefer the nativemilkweed?

We are very exited becaue our class is raising monarch caterpillars!!!  We have done this twice before and once we even got a very small egg.  Last year they came out at a perfect time!We got to see about 5 monarchs emerge in 30 minutes.  We loved it!  At our school in May and August you can step outside and see their fluttering presence.  Once at my house I caught one and it went onto my nose!It tickled like crazy!      Mrs.Buss'4th grade G.T. class

This morning, my 4 year old daughter, Annalise, & I found 16 tiny larvae (just hatched) and 3 that were approx. 1 inch in length on 3 Asclepias currasavica plants in our back yard.  We have not seen any of the adults passing through.

We counted over 215 fourth and fifth instar monarch caterpillars in our 700 square foot atrium.  We have approximately 200 milkweed plants--12 old ones and the rest are new ones.  It was awsome to see one day the milkweed was full of leaves and the next they were bare sticks!

Have about 20 baby caterpillars that are between 1 and 10 cm long.  Am finding eggs daily and most are on the young flower buds of the milkweed while some are on the leaves. We are also starting to find some young caterpillars on the milkweed, which is abundant this spring, as are all the wildflowers!

I have been seeing a few monarchs here in Houston in my gardenbut yesterday 4/12/01 I began to see lot of the caterpillars.I was planting some new plants and there were some big fat caterpillars eating up the milkweed plants. I put about 4 pots of the a. currassivica in the rearing cage and added about 10 caterpillars some of which are in the 5th instar.  Today in another part of the yard, I found about 10 more so I guess the monarchs are making their way in the world. In my rearing cage today, I noticed two of the larva are already getting ready to pupate.  It won't be long until I won't have any milkweed plants left.........Pat in Houston
The larva are eating and the milkweed is growing fast. 8in.I will bring all the larva inside as we are going to be down in the low 30s tomorrow night.
I finally found a single first instar larva today.  There are very few eggs even.  The caterpillar however, did look very pale in color compared to other larva I've seen.
Many chewed milkweed leaves and second or third instar caterpillars.  Sighted by adults.

first larva at this site hatched on 4/22, a day with a high of 81 F. eggs were laid on the 13th.  Most nights since they were laid have been in the 50's with a few in the 30's. Days ranged from 52 F to 81 F with most days near 70 F.
We've had fewer monarchs this year. Lots of other species, however.

On today's date a local visitor brought in the first Monarch larva to the museum.  She actually watched the Monarch lay eggs on her butterflyweed [A tuberosa].  However, she did not leave her phone number so we could ask back for the date.  The larva are 3rd instar in size already.
2 larvae just emerged from their eggs today.

Yesterday I reported bringing 19 eggs back to school (See JN post on Mequon - May 27th  --- FIRST EGGS). Today 5 larva have emerged and are eating well on leaves from our school's milkweed cache which is now about 2 - 3 feet tall -- so the grandchildren have indeed returned.  The kids will get to see them tomorrow as school wasn't in session today -- Happy Memorial Day.Steve K.

Eighteen of the 20 larva which I collected last weekend have emerged and all look very healthy. Eating daily and growing rapidly.  3 students will act as foster parents for the next two weeks and hopefully all the adults will take to the skies on our last day of school - June 13th

I found a Monarch larva, about 3/4 inches long along in our common ground and brought him into raise, with advise from Monarch Watch.  He has molted twice and is now (06/05/01) about two inches long and seems quite fat and happy.
All of the eggs that were gathered May 26 hatched May 30 and 31st.  New eggs that I did not gather, but left in the yard, hatched June 4.

I saw the first monarch butterfly of the season yesterday 6/7/01 around 4o'clock in the afternoon. The wings were worn out and torn a little bit. The butterfly was resting on a flower. It was a miraculous sight.

Of the 20 eggs we had in the classroom 18 have hatched and the larva (10) are now in chrysalids and 6 are in the "J" stage, with 2 still eating away.  All larva and chrysalids are looking very healthy. However in feeding the larva we came up with several more eggs on the feeder milkweed so we still have one egg and (6) 1-2 day-old larva eating voraciously. Adults in two weeks.  It should be noted that I found many eggs on the feeder leaves that I  left intact.

While waiting at a stoplight on Hyw 55 and Wirth Pkwy, I spotted a nice large milkweed plant growing among the uncut grass on the median strip.  I jumped out (in the pouring rain) and snapped off the top of the 3 foot plant and through it in the backseat where my kids quickly spotted one larva and 2 eggs.

Well, today one of the eggs I saw has hatched and a tiny first instar caterpillar has emerged.  Haven't seen an adult still but there must be one somewhere.We have been waiting so long, this is quite a thrill.
Saw the first worm and is very tiny

While doing our Larval Monitoring Pat Landry and I found our 1st first instars and one second instar monarch butterfly larvae at Peninsula Point, Hiawatha National Forest.  Nights are still cool (sometimes in the 40's) and slow development of the eggs we spotted three weeks ago.
eggs wre laid about June 8th,so 14 days to hatchis an indicator of the cool spell we have had.

A few weeks ago I planted some dill, parsley and fennel in individual pots because I had read that these herbs were host plants to butterfly larva.~ Not long after that I saw my first Monarch butterfly. Last saturday, June 23, 2001 I noticed these small 1/2" black and white striped caterpillars. I was quite concerned, because I had never seen this type before. Since they were new to me, I left them alone and decided to keep an eye of them. Boy, am I ever glad I did that!!~Today, June 26, 2001, I was watering the dill, parsley and fennel and I noticed that the caterpillers (larva) had black, cream and yellowish stripes. I was so excited because I realized that they were Monarch larva. I counted them, as they happily munched away, and found about a dozen of them.~I am anxious to watch them go through their different stages of life and can't wait until they become beautiful Monarch flying flowers:)
4th Instar Monarch Larva on common milkweed plant

Driving along our gravel road near our house I noticed a spot where the milkweed leaves seemed to have a lot of chewed areas so I got out of the car and found 4 caterpillars right away.  They were sized from about 1 1/2" to about 1".  Walking down the road towards home I saw at least 5 butterflies hanging on the undersides of the plants and speculate they were laying more eggs.  I've never seen an egg, but found about 5 more catepillars.  One was very small, only about 3/8" long but most were between 1" or larger.The first monarch I saw was June 11th.  Is this about the normal time lapse between eggs and caterpillars?
Located one Monarch Catipilar on a milkweed plant in the city of Ashland, WI.

Monarch larvae are very abundant on the Sanctuary's milkweed plants.  Much size variation exists among larvae, from less than a 1/4" in length to pupating stage.Also during the last week of June, red admirals were extremely abundant and feeding on flowering wild sumac.
school: Wetlands, pines and prairie audubon sanctuary

comments: I discovered 4 Monarch larva on the walkway to the lighthouse in South Haven,Michigan while I was there on vacation. Two larvae were large and ready to form chyrsalids in a short time. The other two were very small.  There was also a large growth of milkweed on the walkway.
Spent late afternoon going in and out of an 8' hedge row.

There was tiny amount of new growth on eaten-up milkweed plant left from fall. Saw one caterpillar. Many chrysalids in backyard and hanging from garage siding and eave of house found last month (early January).

Four larvae have emerged today from the 15 eggs collected March 11 and 13 on the playground of Jackson Elementary School in McAllen, TX.  Students at Weslaco East High School in Weslaco, TX, will be raising the larvae and releasing the adults.

We had 12 babies born today, and more should greet us tomorrow.  Milkweed is still kind of scarce here in Austin but in San Marcos just south of here it is growing at a faster rate.  We have also observed and are monitoring approx. 75 eggs that as of today have yet to emerge.  t

Asclepias asperula, a native milkweed and growing wild in DeWitt County, has been "loaded" with eggs this week.  First plant we checked had three stems (twelve, fourteen, and eighteen leaves) with nine eggs and one first instar.  An informal county on one hundred stems (average of twelve leaves) yielded one hundred eggs and the one larva.  ... see Monarch Egg (FIRST sighted) ...
I have 2 larva that just hatched in captivity.  I have looked for any strays on the milkweed but have not seen any but I did bring in two more leaves today 03/29 with an egg on each leaf.

My son and his classmates were given a small caterpillar on a milkweed plant.  The caterpillar made his crysalis the night of March 29th and early March 30th.  He is doing great and the children are enjoying what nature is producing.

My son and his classmates were given a small caterpillar on a milkweed plant.  The caterpillar made his crysalis the night of March 29th and early March 30th.  He is doing great and the children are enjoying what nature is producing.
I did find a monarch caterpillar in my yard today so that is good news.

A group of students from Mississippi College found 33 eggs and a single first instar larva this afternoon (4 April, 2002) at the Choctaw Trails site in southwest Jackson. The larva had just emerged and had partially eaten its egg shell; the leaf on which this partial shell was located also had another partial shell indicating a second larva had also hatched but that one was not located. No adults were observed this afternoon and due to the lower temperatures on April 3 and April 4, it is unlikely that oviposition has occured since the 2nd.
First larva was seen today around 9:00 a.m.  The eggs that were found on Friday Have hatched.  By afternoon several more could be found.
I saw 3 larva today.

For the past three weeks there have been very faded monarchs in our area.  However we have had a very cool spring and our milkweed (asclepias virdis)is only about 7" at present. I have covered acres and only found two larva.  The Monarchs are still in the area...Maybe they were just waiting around for the sun!Sure hope they are mating and we will see more larva soon.

I am so excited!!!!!  Today I counted 27 little larvea almost 1/4" long on my swamp milkweed which is only about 4-5" tall.  I hope to keep the plant real healthy.  I also hope the weather stay warm.  I was worried about them coming since the big loss in Mexico.  Yea!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
A larvae in the second instar was found on 12" high swamp milkweed. By the looks of the leaves another larvae was eating and lost - maybe to a bird. What excitement!!

A group of 11 7th graders from St. Mary's school in Oak Ridge are participating in a research project in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park.  We went on our first trip today and found Monarch larva on a few milkweed plants in Cades Cove.

have 4 milkweed plants.   I have seen no eggs on any of them, but two have had 1st instar caterpillars, 1 on one plant and 3 on another.  I also have never seen those caterpillars or any others at any stage, let alone 2+ instars.  Predation must be wicked in my yard!Sigrid Benson, Gulf Breeze, FL

We live at 1600 feet altitude and I have a clone of 41 stems of Asclepias syriaca growing in my front garden. The shoots are mostly about 14 inches high, very healthy, and about half are in the early bud stage.

On 11 May 2002, I counted about 15 young first instar larvae on the plants, almost all feeding on the apical leaves surrounding the buds, or where the buds will shortly appear. No eggs or older first instars or any other larvae were noted and I suspect that all 15 were from eggs laid by a single female passing through.

To estimate the date of egg laying; the 1st instar larvae were atleast 2 days old; the eggs probably at least 4, so the eggs would have tohave been laid on or before 4 May 2002. (1 May seems earliest possibleestimate).

Small round holes chewed in several other leaves indicated that there were originally about 20 larvae. On 12 May, I rechecked the plants and most, if not all, had disappeared, almost certainly eaten by predators. I have not yet seen any adult monarchs in this part of Virginia. I think it is a good idea, especially this year, to do as Elizabeth Hunter did: bring eggs and

Finally found some Monarch caterpillars.  The weather has been cold and rainy, and we just had not seen any signs of caterpillars.  These must have been eating somewhere, as they are already well on their way.

Found (3) first instar caterpillars on milkweed collected to feed our classroom caterpillars. Returned to the site to search more throughly and found (1) more. Milkweed was heavily infested with aphids, ants, ladybugs, and earwigs. Fear that any other may have fallen prey to other insects. But, will keep looking!
A single 3rd or 4th instar monarch caterpillar was found on a Butterfly weed plant at the Montessori Community School.

Found 5 larva feeding on milkweed,each approx. 1.5 cm long (i.e., several days out of egg. We have removed these leaves to interior location, where we will be raising these caterpillers until they reach adult stage, at which time they will be freed. On aprox. 2 dozen milkweed plants in our side yard (we live in a residential area, there are approx. 24 eggs, layed by one or two adult females, as they are not all of the same maturity. We will observe until hatching and raise as many as possible. This has been a yearly project for my daughters and I for about 8 years. Starting with one larva first year, we have raised increasing numbers each year. Last year, we raised 35+ larva over approx. 3 generations through the summer. This is the heaviest first egg batch I have observed to date. I hope we can increase the proportion of eggs that hatch and grow to maturity over the usual odds.

In my first site, a natural park, setting, there had been nine eggs but I only saw two larva, and no more eggs. It looked like there had been more larva, as the milkweed leaves had marks, but could not find the larva.The second site, a park, which has over 50 milkweed plants, had several eggs and I found one larva, busily munching on the milkweed.The third site, I found two eggs, and one larva, which I am raising at home, and will release it at the site, a pond site with over 20 milkweed.The fourth site, near agricultural fields, has no eggs/no larva.T
Larva hatched this morning!!
A first instar was found on Friday.  Of the eggs collected I now have 12 first instars.

The 15 eggs I gathered on the 30th hatched sometime last night and are now in a large container.  They are about the size of the small "i" of this type.   When I went to gather milkweed for them there were two more eggs on the plant I gathered.  I haven't yet seen the monarch near my farm, but obviously they have been here.

I had a monarch lay eggs on June 1st in my garden, but unfortunately a rabbit mowed down most of the milkweed.  One egg did survive and just hatched on June 10th.  I have the larva in my house and am raising it to keep it away from predators.

One of my students brought a larva to school that was approximately one week old.  She lives on a farm that is in the path of the migration and witnesses the monarchs resting in her trees each season.  She told me approximately one month ago that she saw a monarch but I didn't report it because I wasn't sure she could accurately identify the species. The caterpillar she brought to me yesterday was definitely a monarch on a milkweed leaf.
Today I found my a first instar caterpillar. I noticed evidence of eating and then found the little one. It is now safely under my care.

two eggs that i brought in on sunday have hatched and are feeding on the milkweed they are on. i have placed milkweed in with them from my garden which i washed to make sure there is no BTK on them. we have alot of rain hopefully that will wash away the BTK and some of the butterfly larvas will survive. the whole lake has been sprayed at least twice. even though we are against it there are signs of it on our propertydue to the high winds when the spraying was done.six mile lake, muskoka
15 late 1st instar/early 2nd instar found by three people in one hour of search time
Found 3 large caterpillars.  I've looked for several weeks in many milkweed patches in Connecticut.  I saw one monarch last week in Groton,CT and no eggs.
Gathered 45 eggs.
Gathered 25 larva, various instars.
Found 3 - 1st instar caterpillars - July 3rdFound 2 - 5th instar caterpillars - July 4thOne caterpillar changed into a chrysalis this morning and the second one will tomorrow.
We have 6 larvae on our milkweed plant.
Young caterpillar on a new milkweed plant in my garden, first I have seen this summer.
This morning, I found my first larva, a fifth instar,  on asclepsia incarnata actively feeding.  Plenty of milkweed available but declining with a heavy aphid infestation and also milkweed bugs.
Found 6 monarch larva
Saw a monarch caterpillar in our front yard on our milkweed plant this morning, 2-11-03.  It was about 2 inches in length.

My neighbors have hungry caterpillars mnching away on their butterfly weeds. These ladies garden for buttterflys. These caterpillars must be from over wintering Monarchs, but I have seen more adults in the past 2 weeks.
Our first catapillar hatched! It is so tiny.
Found 50 eggs on 24 A. oenotheroides, 6 1st. instar caterpillars.
school: Rio bravo nature center foundation, inc

comments: While checking Asclepias viridis patch for eggs (east of Victoria proper) a seventh grader that had joined me (mom and little brother too) found hatchling monarch larvae.  Many, many eggs over the three acre patch.  Two faded monarch females came by as we were visiting 'their' milkweed patch.  Monarch eggs should be hatching on Asclepias asperula in northwestern DeWitt County.  Many eggs there, watched two very faded monarch females there an hour earlier depositing eggs.  These should be monarchs from Mexico and not from winter crop along the coast.  What the fire ants let grow to maturity should be "generation two" heading north in about thirty days.

We had not been finding larvae from the batch of eggs that the monarchs deposited a week ago, so we went out this afternoon and checked over a hundred stems of curassavica (did find about a hundred "new" eggs).  We found four first instars on curassavica and one on syriaca plus one rather plump larva that was going into the third instar ... one made it!  There were six sites on the  bottom of leaves, where we expected fifty, that had the tell-tale, chewed circle and latex "mustache" of a hatchling.  Something is getting the eggs and we have some nominees.  We found a very active nest of fireants in the curassavica bed (one painful bite!) and even some over on the deck plus wood ants and snails.  Two dozen eggs are now inside.

While cleaning one of my flower beds a counted 5 monarch caterpilars/larves less than an inch long on my butterfly weed/milkweed. The plant has yet to bloom but has buds. I'm sure there's more than 5 judging by the amount of leaves that have been eaten & I've been out of town for the past week.

The weather was cold and clear.  The low temperature last night was 34 degrees.  Upon observation of the milkweed plants, students discovered tiny Monarch larva.  All of the egg cases were gone from the leaves.

I did my survey this afternoon and on the 29 plants and only found 28 eggs all looking like they are ready to pop out.  I found three wee 1st instars.  I have a feeling that the missing numbers are there in instar stage and that I missed them, (18).
While searching for eggs this afternoon I spotted the frist larva of the season.  It was a first instar, apparently just leaving its eaten shell.  It was found on a good sized asclepias viridis.
12 first instars were found on Asclepias viridis at Choctaw Trails today.
We have between 9 and 15 caterpillars ranging in age from one day to about 5 days old. Hope we have enough milkweed to keep them all fed until chrysalis stage!

Seventh periodWe have found eight to ten monarch caterpillars that around two centimeters in length. We did not notice these caterpillars on Monday, April 7th, when we last checked the milkweed. They have eaten most of the milkweed. We have also found that some of the caterpillars have moved to a broccoli plant and they appear to be eating the pods of the plant. We are going to observe the caterpillars on the broccoli plant and see if they continue eating it.  At this time there does not seem to be enough milkweed for all of the caterpillars.
Two first instar larvae sighted on butterfly milkweed outside Mt. Magazine State Park Visitor Center, Logan County.

My fourth graders had planted milkweed in the fall and were excited in March to see it sprouting. It had gotten about a foot and a half tall when we were out for Easter holidays. Last Wed. another class spotted 2 Monarchs sitting on one of our milkweed plants. Today we went out to check for eggs and were supprised to see most of our plants were eaten down! When we looked closer, the plants were covered with tiny Monarch caterpillars. There are around 30 of them, with more eggs to hatch. We only have about 10 plants, so we are scrambing to find more milkweed in the area. We located 30 more small plants at a nursery this afternoon, so we will plant them tomorrow. My students are so excited and can't wait to begin measuring and videoing our caterpillars. We begin standardized testing tomorrow, so we will have something fun to relax us in the afternoon. We feel like new parents!!
Several of the 52 eggs are hatching.Our first grade class is excited.
Found Monarch caterpillars on milkweed in the meadow today.  All one half inch or smaller, some with just discernable stripes.  Leaves slightly munched on these plants.

6 hatchings of larvae today even though temps were in the 60s.  First eggs were sighted 8 days ago and the weather since the laying has been unusually cool.  There may not be enough common milkweed to go around to feed the 60 eggs that have been laid on approx. 20 plants!

I checked the milkweeds this morning to see how the eggs were doing, and I saw babies!!!!!  The larvae were about 1 to 2 centimeters long.  They were happily eating on the milkweed.  They weathered a bad storm early Sunday morning, still eating.  We will keep an eye on them to see how they progess.

We estimate the larva to be about 1 wk. old.  Last year we hatached monarchs, and documented the growth of the larva. From these measurements is how we have aged this larva.  This caterpiller was found at the butterfly garden at Tri-Valley Elementary located in Downs.

I had my first monarch egg hatch today off my swamp milkweed.  I will raise it in captivity and let it go when it is mature.  I have never had a monarch caterpillar make it to butterfly on the plants in my yard.
We are finding quite a few young larvae (lst through third instars) on milkweed now, and fresh females are ovipositing throughout Tarrant county (Ft.Worth,etc.).
Saw first caterpillar of the season.
Three second-instar larva were found in the butterfly garden. There were 11 eggs last week...now only one egg and three larva (21 milkweed plants examined thoroughly).

I was out checking the garden and saw some small chew marks in the   very small milkweed(8 inches high) which I moved about 2 weeks ago. I was very surprised to find 3 monarch caterpillars.  I found a fourth in another patch on another small common milkweed.  This is the earliest day I have ever found a  caterpillar...My finds are usally in the later part of July.  (I brought them in to raise and hopefully to breed and have more caterpillars for my  butterfly class in July.) So I guess a few weeks ago a monarch passed thru without me seeing it...
One of the eggs found on Thursday, May 29th has hatched.  There is now a first instar on our plant.
One caterpillar in first instar found on Asclepias Syriaca.

Weather has been really cool this year.  We had one day last week dropping down to 42 degrees and several other nights dropping down into the 40's.  Nurseries were advising not to plant tender plants until after Memorial Day due to the temperatures.  Milkweed in my garden is about 8" tall.  I saw some leaves chewed and checked the milkweed out.  Found 5 baby monarch caterpillars about a quarter inch long.  They are on my 'Ice Ballet' and 'Cinderella' swamp milkweed.  None are on my Tuberosa which is the first place I found them last year.
While on a butterfly hike at Burr Oak Woods in Blue Springs, I observed several monarc caterpillars munching on milkweed.  It was exciting!  I had been looking for several weeks.
We have four baby caterpillars on our orange milkweed plants. The monarch layed her eggs on May 28th and we first saw the caterpillars on Monday. They are eating away.
There are many 2nd instar larva on the milkweed in my yard.  There are usually 2 on each plant hiding way up among the tiny top leaves, but my milkweed is dotted with holes!

Found another caterpillar at the College of Dupage in Glen Ellyn, IL. It looked like it was in the third star range. It was huge! This is so exciting. I usually don't see caterpillars until around the first week in July. But then again, I never looked this hard before.

Contributed by Monarch Watch
A second instar monarch caterpillar was seen feeding on milkweed,asclepias incarnata, around 9 am.  There are 10 mature milkweedplants at this site, later today I will check the rest for cats.
first instar on milkweed leaf.  84 degrees F.  south-facing slope in full sunlight.

YIPPEE! was really starting to worry  Found just one hopefully more to come. He was about a quarter inch long. Does anyone know why it took so long this year? Was it the cooler weather we experienced this year?
Found my first larva on swamp milkweed.Larva seemed to have just hatched.
A fully developed larva
one small larva sighted on leafed out milkweed

I found a cacooon for a monarch on my Persian shield plant.  It is located very close to a bunch of butterfly weed I have.  Today 2/16 it is still in the cacoon stage but I will watch and let you know if and when it comes out.
I found the larva outside on a milkweed plant.  The weather was clear and the temperatures outside were between 70-74 degrees.

There has not been a freeze at my location this winter. Therefore, I still have 2 milkweed plants with a few leaves.  About 6 weeks ago, I saw a Monarch lay eggs on these plants;  but have seen nothing since.  Today I saw 4 larvae close to full size on the plants.

First Monarch caterpillar on my Milkweed today. Must have missed him earlier this week because he is very large already. The first Monarch I saw on 2/23 was laying eggs on the Milkweed.Spring is here in Central Florida.

Just a little correction/addition to the above report. I went out to take a picture of the Monarch caterpillar and found 8 small ones on the Milkweed in addition to the large one. Hope I have enough Milkweed to make them all happy!

3/19/04 Just wanted to update you. I have 25 Monarch caterpillar on my Milkweedright now and think several of the 1st ones I saw have already gone to thenext stage. I may have to go buy some additional large Milkweed to supportthem:)I have lots of Milkweed seedlings started for later in the year.
We have seen two monarch caterpillars.

One of the lady monarchs I've been watching in Tallahassee has turned productive: I counted 39 eggs and three 2nd instar caterpillars this morning. This is the earliest I've found eggs in the last five springs.(Also reported in monarch egg.)

Were they laying eggs, if so on what species of milkweed?: yes--counted 32caterpillars. purchased more Butterfly Weed so they would have enough to eattheir last day of munching Butterfly Weed Asclepias tuberosa(Asclepiadaceae

Nevertheless, my milkweed is growingvery well and will be able to support more caterpillars.

Did an inventory in the backyard about an hour ago and found the following: - A single adult monarch (not worn) laying eggs on A. Curassavica - Seven large (sorry, I don't know what instar) monarch caterpillars I have about 20-30 milkweed plants, all Curassavicas.

We did see some monarch a coupleweeks ago. No great migration, just one here and there. This morning I wastrimming the lantana and lo and behold I counted over a dozen monarchcaterpillars and just had to share the great news with someone.

We have four monarch caterpillars that just went into chrysalis stage in my garden and now we wait for the arrival of the beautiful adult monarchs.

I do not usually get many larvae on the Journey North.  However, thispast weekend, I counted 12 larvae in one milkweed-plant grouping. Fivehave since hung and turned into chrysalis.  At least four more are outthere and have chosen secretive hanging spots that I've yet to find.The rest are still churning away at the plants.  Four climbed all theway to the eaves of the house, the fifth has found a large pot thatseems an ideal place to hang as well.  I have probably around 10 larvaein the 1/2 to 1 inch size scattered in four locations.  The abundanceI'm seeing on my plants is definitely up from last year. Firstly, lastyear, I had very little milkweed as it froze to the ground, unlike thisyear when it never died back.  Only one butterfly; looked fairly new andshe laid just a few eggs this weekend that I saw.  I tend to see moreegg-laying done on the migration south than going north, so this isquite a decent number for my garden this year. I think I am on theeastern edge of the northbound route. Plus, this observation in mygarden would probably concur with the consensus that they haven't movedvery far East yet.  I had one larvae that was most unusual.  It lookedlike someone had sliced it down the back and then stitched it up again,it was most unusual.  My only thought on this is that perhaps it got inthe nearby rose bush and walked under a thorn which maybe did thedamage.  Any ideas?
We counted 12 caterpillars about 1 inch long in our butterfly garden.  A 13th appeared to be the victim of a spider at half that length.

Haven't looked specifically for eggs but we havehosted 9 caterpillars to date on butterflyweed(asclepias tuberosa)

April 6 update: Our caterpillar level has been ashigh as 18 on the milkweed.

Larva found on wild milkweed growing along Highway 16 northwest of Helotes and San Antonio.  There is plenty of milkweed in the area this year.  I have not seen adult butterflies yet.  My students (gifted 1-5th grade) have collected 28 eggs and hatched that many larva in the classroom.  Last year we hatched and released 968 butterflies including 911 Monarchs and 57 Queens.  Each release was photographed and the photo and a student letter weresent to a family who lost someone in the 9/11 terrorist attack. Our goal is to raise and release a butterfly for each of the 3006 people lost.  It will take us a long time but the students enjoy the butterflies.

have become very interested in the monarchbutterflies that come each year to some plants I have in my front yard (in aprotected place). I can't recall the name of the plants (yellow flowers),but ever since I planted them about 2 years ago, we've had eggs,caterpillars, pupae a few places, and then hopefully butterflies. I'mfascinated by the process. Yesterday I counted probably 10 caterpillars onthe plants, and the plants have been completely eaten now, all except thestalks. I've seen only two pupae so far, but expect to see more.

we saw a monarch caterpillar on my great-grandmother's milkweed...it was eating a leaf...Alexandra...7 years old

Today while mowing the lawn, I noticed that they were looking scrawny so I went for a closer look and was thrilled to discover at least 20 monarch caterpillars feasting on the plants.  Needless to say, I will be buying more plants to keep them eating.  This is my first time to have milkweed in my yard and I am thrilled with these caterpillars.  I will enjoy checking their progress every day.

Just wanted to let you know we had a single female Monarch in our yard today,May 13, and I harvested 31 eggs from my milkweed plants. My next doorneighbor also brought in a number of leaves. This is the earliest I have ever foundeggs, and I was lucky to beat a thunder storm a few hours later.

I found the first larva Friday evening 5/14/04. I have not seen any Monarch Butterflies this spring. I have been waiting and watching but nothing. I found 4 about 3 days old. I looked on about 30 knee high plants and did not find a single egg. I'll keep looking.

Everyone! We found a 2nd instar cat on tuberosa at the Master Gardener's Demo Gardens in Frederick Maryland. This is a truly unreal find. We not seen monarchs yet. (50 miles north of DC.) Especially this early! Where did the little guy come from?

Second instar, found on Oak Knoll Rd near Cty Hwy K

The garden is new this spring so needless to say, I am very excited!
Saw my first Monarch caterpillar since I was a boy in Illinois.  Here I am working the midnight shift and thought that I would search the Internet for sites that talk about Monarch butterflies.
Found my first newly-hatched larva of the season on a common milkweed in our wildflower garden.

My first egg hatched today. I expect two more to hatch shortly. I also found one of the eggs in the flower head.

Have seen occasional monarchs through the spring butsaw my first monarch caterpillar of the season today,about a 3rd instar.

-I found three 2nd instar monarch cats feeding on our swamp milkweed plant, near the kitchen window.  All 3 were brought inside for hand rearing.  In previous years, we have lost most of the monarch cats to ants, so now I hand rear them.
We have lots of milkweed on our property.  I just started to see larvae
I found 6 third instar monarch caterpillars in my milkweed patch of 45 plants.  Have not seen a Monarch butterfly yet.
we have at least a dozen new larvae in the butterfly garden.  very small.

Good things take time.  Just now I have seen my first adult today.  We have been having south westerly winds and rain,perhaps it flew in on the wind.  I don't know,but it sure perked me up,big time.  Just about 4 p.m. with flluffy white clouds and bright a blue sky.

We discovered 3 larvae that are about 5-7 days old on our milkweed.  We did not see the adult who laid the eggs and we were very surprised to see the larvae.  Usually we don't see Monarchs until the end of July.

We have three Monarch larvae on our milkweed.  We were surprised to see them and we did not see the adult.  They are about 7 days old.  We don't usually see Monarchs until the end of July so we were pleasantly surprised to notice that something was eating our milkweed and that something were Monarch larvae.

I had not seen any Monarch catapillers all summer on the milkweed I planted to specifically bring them to my backyard. I came back from a weekend vacation and there were cats all over my milkweed. I counted 16 total. They are soo cute!

I'm in Clearwater, FL just a few miles north of St. Pete.I have observed quite a few larva in my Milkweed patch.In fact they have just about cleared each plant of leaves.

I also grow milkweed in pots and bring them inside wheni see larvae on them. I currently have about 6 in pupaeform now. I have observed a few chrysalis that have beenlost to Tachinid flies.

During the warm weather of the past few weeks i've alsoobserved many male Monarchs in my yard. Up to five orsix of them at a time chasing each other around all day.

Contributed to Monarch Watch

The annual January monarch larva explosion is once again occurring here in my backyard habitat in St. Petersburg, FL. I have recovered over 100 5th instar larva from the wild over the past two weeks. I began discovering the larva around the first of the year. Prior to that, very few reached maturity. Temperatures here have been 8-9 degrees above normal for the past two weeks, but now have dipped to their norms of 65-70 degrees daytime to 50-55 degrees or thereabouts at night.

The larva are forming pupae as I write. They appear, for the most part, full sized and healthy. If anyone else in FL is observing the same situation with monarch larva, perhaps they could post a report.

Contributed to Monarch Watch

My mother called yesterday and reported 2 catapillars in her garden in Houston, Texas- a little early isn't it?

Contributed to Monarch Watch

We have several asclepias plants in our backyard in order to attract Monarch larvae. There are about 8 larvae of various sizes on the plants now. One has gone to the pupa stage. Last September, 2004, all of the pupae turned brown and died. We don't know why. I hope that doesn't happen again to this generation.

I reported three monarch caterpillars spotted this weekend but don't think it got recorded soI'm putting it in again.  I have very little milkweed but have found two very large caterpillars and one small one on the milkweed.  They were brought inside and will be raised to adults.There are quite a few eggs on the milkweed but not many leaves so I will have to hunt for some in the neighborhood.  I don't know if the monarch butterfies were overwintering or if they mighthave migrated from the south as I didn't see any during the previous months.

Wandering my garden, I noticed a plant completely void of leaves.  When I looked closer, I noticed 8 monarch larva on adjacent plants.  I moved the larva over to a neighboring milkweed.  (I had forgotten I planted the milkweed last fall.)  One of the larva is a 3rd instar, 4 appear to be second instar and the last seems to be a 1st instar.  There are also numerous eggs on the remaining milkweed.  I don't know if there is enough foliage to support all of the larva so I may buy some plants and put them out nearby.

one larve about 1 inch long. Also sighted an adult flying through the yard.  It did not stop to nectar while I was out there.

I have not seen any monarchs yet BUT we went to our summer cottage and I found a newly hatched pillar on the Asclepsia syracia on Monday June 20th. Three days ago (March 5), my youngest son noticed 2 'very-newly-hatched' (less than 1/4" long)monarch caterpillars on the only milkweed bush in our butterfly garden that hadn't been pruned back in fall.

I have had over-wintering monarchs here in ZipCode 77068. I found several newly hatched Monarch caterpillars on Antelope horns near [6 miles northwest of] Helotes. They were eating the eggshells. Six were collected and taken on 3/20/06 to Timberwilde Elementary School [Northside ISD] where they will be reared  abd released by my students.  Since 9/11 my Gifted and Talented students have been working on a public service project to release a butterfly for each individual killed in the terrorist attacks.  They have released 1697 butterflies todate.  By far the majority have been Monarchs.  We have also raised Queens, Giant Swallowtails, Eastern Black Swallowtails, Pipevine Swallowtails and 2 moths.

Caller reports about 30 larvae (all stages, many mature) on 10 A.curassavica plants in her yard near Katy (on IH-10 w. of Houston). All of her plants are now stripped but she was able to buy 5 more bushy A.c.plants. She reports having a few monarchs year-round.

Due to our warm weather here in Jacksonville, Florida, we've seen adult monarchs all year.  Our milkweeds also have never lost all their leaves.  One plant is already blooming, others are close. (Time to plant the parsley for the black swallowtails!)

We are in Houston, TX and currently have 64 monarch caterpillars that are devouring the plants I have. The count is rising each day. About 1/2 of the caterpillars are full size. The kids thought it was hysterical. We moved him outside with the others.

Went to a nursery to get more milkweed, while there a very tattered female was laying eggs all over the incarnata and glory flower.  I wound up buying more than I had planned and i talked so much about it to others there that by the time I left i am sure they sold out!  Five plants and over 30 larva. The caterpillars on the outside plant are much smaller, which isn't surprising since we had several days of heavy rain which must have interfered with eating.  The ones in the house are eating all the milkweed-will have to make a trip back to that nursery. <G>.  Problem is the butterfly house I have inside isn't big enough for all this activity, otherwise i would have brought them all inside.

Found what appeared to be a late 2nd Instar Larva near Whitehouse, Ohio feeding on Common Milkweed (Asclepias syriaca).  The egg itself was probably deposited around the 26th of May; hatched in three days due to the very warm and sometimes wet weather we have been experiencing; had its 1st molt and has been growing steadily ever since on an abundance of great-looking milkweed. Also located on the milkweed in this field after just a few minutes of looking.  Returned to the Lourdes College Campus in the early evening and found two 1st Instar Monarch Larvae on milkweed growing in the Prairie Garden.  Although I didn't check the Swamp (incarnata), Butterfly Weed (tuberosa) or Common Milkweed in our nearby Life Lab Garden because it was late in the day, there should be eggs and larvae to be seen when daylight returns tomorrow.

We found three milkweed plants in The Orchard at Altapass butterfly garden with about 20 third instar monarch caterpillars all over them.  The plants were growing close together. During the next 7 days, another 25 caterpillars were found (in or near the garden), with some in 5th instar, and many eggs and tiny caterpillars. We continue to find eggs and little caterpillars in very large numbers, and have 3 terrariums filled with 37 chrysalises. We lost 7 that had been parasitized. During that time, we saw 1 adult monarch in the area, and 1 five miles away. The milkweed plants are especially stout (thick stemmed) and vigorous.

3/24/07 - Found our first monarch larva today! A newborn first instar (less than 2mm) long on an Asclepias viridis plant.3/26/07 - Today I had the chance to make an inventory of the milkweed patches on about 2 acres of mostly native grassland (used as a horse pasture off and on). The results were: 129 individual milkweed plants with 1 or more monarch eggs attached, 159 eggs (about 6 ready to open), and 9 first instar caterpillars. Most plants had 1 egg, 22 plants had 2 eggs, and 4 plants had 3 eggs. While outside this morning (for approx. 90 min.) I observed 5 monarchs: 3 flying and 2 faded females actively egg-laying. Today is overcast and 75 degrees F.
there are about 7 larva on 5 of our milkweed plants

Larvae are hatching from eggs collected at the Choctaw Trails site in southwest Jackson. 88 eggs have been collected from 3 separate quick outings(44, 25, 19) with the most recent collection of 19 eggs yesterday afternoon (March 27). No larvae had emerged as of 5 pm yesterday but numerous individual small larvae are present today. No larvae have been observed in the field.

A single monarch larva was observed on Asclepias viridis yesterday afternoon (March 28) at the Choctaw Trails site in southwest Jackson, MS. Earlier in the day hatching was observed in specimens collected from this site and maintained in the lab. I have been posting images of the eggs and now the larva daily at the Clinton Community Nature Center website, http://www.clintonnaturecenter.org/Default.htm
Larva on A. currasavica in garden
2 second instars found as I monitored my milkweed this week.
I have about 7 or 8 monarch caterpillars on my container milkweed garden. 4-5 of them I suspect will be in chrysalis form before the end of the week.
2 - 1st instars found.

On the way back to Abilene yesterday, every plant had both eggs and 1st instar caterpillars. Buds were larger and almost ready to open in just 3 days. The area had recieved upwards of 7" of rain recently. Plants had between 9 and 15 ramettes and I counted 9 eggs on one of the larger plants. The ramettes were from just a few inches in height to 14", starting to spread out from the center and lay along the ground with the weight of the budding heads.

Courtesy of Monarch Watch

I saw my first monarch of the year last Wednesday in Burnsville and my friend Judy C's husband Bill saw one on or about the same day near where they live. However, we have had 20 degree temps the last two nights (another predicted for tonight) and woke yesterday (April 7th) to 2-3 inches of SNOW. Snow melted during the day, so nothing except the plants I covered before it turned cold had any protection last night. I am sure that returning monarch--the earliest I have ever seen here--died in the cold. SO depressing!

Our spring, which was proceeding so beautifully, has been ruined. Trees that had begun to leaf out all got burned, cherry in full bloom now has brown blossoms. Judy and Bill lost their whole apple crop in their 80-acre orchard. What do you think the result of this extended freeze will be on the 2007 monarch season?

Forwarded for Elizabeth H. by Dr. Lincoln Brower.

Thursday, I gathered up about 15 Monarch eggs found on A. incarnata, and A. speciosa and brought them inside. They were predicting freezing temps for this area into the 20's.  I covered what plants I could in my garden, and hoped for the best.  Saturday, I had my 1st Monarch cat hatch.  And, several more on Sunday.  We were quite fortunate that the temps did not stay below freezing very long Saturday morning.  And did not freeze on Sunday.  The milkweed in my garden still looks quite good, as well as the eggs left outside on my covered plants.  I have now brought more eggs in to see how well they hatch.  Ready for warmer weather....

My class found a tiny caterpillar on the milkweed in our butterfly garden. The week before we had watched a female laying eggs on the underside of milkweed leaves. Our school is closed for spring holidays. We are anxious to see what has happened when we return.

Noticed my yellow butterflyweed was torn up. Thought I had beat it up with the weedeater.  Looked closer and found several larvae.  Looked at the orange variety growing closer to the house and there were none.  Will keep an eye on to see where they go to "rest."

I have some milkweed (the one with orange and yellow flowers) that volunteered in a flowerbed.  While I was working in the flowerbed, I discovered 2 monarch caterpiilars.  They are approximately 1-1/2 inches long.  I assume that very soon they will form chrysalis's and make their wonderful transformation.  I have taken photos and am watching and waiting.
First set of 8 eggs laid have hatched into larvae.   There are undoubetly more in the garden!

Our first milkweed and eggs were frozen by the unusually severe cold spell in early April - a multi-day freeze that followed an unusually warm period.  This was our first sighting of larvae since the freeze.
This milkweed had monarch larvae--also on stems and unopened leaves

My children and I found a young 5th instar monarch larva on a healthy green milkweed (Asclepias viridis) plant growing in disturbed tallgrass prairie near our home.  I searched 40 to 50 additional milkweed stems, but found no other signs of eggs or larvae.We took the larva home, and are rearing it.

Latitude & longitude are a bit off.  This was River Farm Park on the Potomac, a bit up the river from the Mount Vernon estate (whose coordinates I actually entered). Earliest larvae I've EVER seen in my area!  I saw over ten; there were likely many more.  Oldest were about 3 days, based on size.  Youngest was newly hatched on May 10 or previous night.  Chewing patterns didn't indicate any larger or older larvae.  None of the milkweed was much taller than 15."  Looked like all incarnata.  Location:  by a river, in a small open meadow, near gardens FULL of flowers.

17May07: This is the first larva to hatch (by 6 am) from the eggs found on Mother's day. See related report on first egg sighting. The other four look like they are ready to hatch today - probably within hours.
Although I have still not seen a monarch (she must be sneaky), I did find eggs on my milkweed yesterday (5/16) and several of the eggs have hatched this morning! :)

I found two larva...one slightly larger than the other on some "swamp milkweed" that I planted several years ago specifically to attract monarchs.  About two or three weeks ago, I saw a monarch in my yard.  I was positive it was a male one. I was so excited to see one this early.  Now, today!  I go out and find two larvae!!! Must have been a female!  The butterfly went to every single milkweed plant...which were only about 2 inches tall at that time!Exciting!

I discovered third instar caterpillars this morning on the Prairie Milkweed (Asclepias sullivantii). This species is close two feet tall now in comparison to many other species I grow that are far behind in growth. In seven years at this location, this is the earliest I have ever had caterpillars. I have not seen a single butterfly anywhere, but obviously a least one female flew through my yard!

Courtesy of Monarch Watch
Saw an adult monarch on my milkweed plants on 05/14/07.  Have checked the eggs daily and today they finally hatched.
Found larva on milkweed by road.  Not very old, was still munching on its egg remains.  Also spotted an abandoned egg but could not find any larva.

Four of the 19 Monarch eggs found on the 21st and 22nd have hatched, late this afternoon and evening.  I'm expecting 7 more to be hatching before midnight.  Two eggs are still really yellow so I'm going to pull those so they don't get eaten.  Nasty T storms this evening along with extremely high winds and a green sky.  Don't know if a tornado or funnel has been confirmed, but I'm sure glad those eggs and larvae are safe inside!  :-)
Tiny caterpillar hatched from egg I collected Tuesday.
Checking my field milkweed, and I found two second instar larva up in the tops of two budding milkweed plants.  I also found 7 eggs.

Today I came home from work to find 5 Monarch eggs that my husband found for me while working. They were found in Grand Haven Township.  One hatched within the hour and several more are ready.  We still have not seen a Monarch butterfly....
One of the eggs on the first milkweed in my yard has hatched, making it the first larva for me this year.

Those 3 eggs I found on Wednesday, May 23rd?  They hatched last night, Saturday, May 26th. So cute, these microscopic mini monarch cats! Between the little milkweed plants growing in my garden, plus the plants out on the road, I should have no shortage of food for these little guys.  But most plants are still really small. No big milkweed plants to feed hungry 5th instar cats!  If, there are more out there. I hope they grow quickly. By the way, hubby came home yesterday & said, "Saw a monarch butterfly at work yesterday,  flying around."  Don works at The Wigamog Inn & Resorst, half way between Haliburton Village & Minden. Louise,Haliburton, ON
The 9 Monarch eggs I found on May 24th hatched today. I have 9 little Monarch caterpillars.
First larvae from collected eggs started hatching last night, and into today.  Not sure if collected eggs count for this, but I thought I'd report anyway.
The larvae were found next to the school.  They were large and seem like they will soon turn into caterpillars.
We saw one larva on a milkweed plant on May 28. It was likely a second instar.  However, I have not found it since and wonder what happened to it.

My four year old and I were checking out the milkweed at the pond near our house, and he spotted our first caterpillar! The milkweed patch was huge, but we couldn't find a single egg or caterpillar on any of the other plants.
Adult female Monarch flying around milkweed laying eggs. Also many caterpillars and eggs found!
I found 3 caterpillars on my milkweeds this AM. One was slightly larger than the other two, but all were very small, hard to spot.

First tiny Monarch caterpillers appeared today (Jun 11, 2007)in my Swamp Milkweed (Asclepius incarnata).  They are hiding in the growing tips of the plants beside the growing flower buds and covered by the new leaves that are still enfolding the flower bud.  They are only 0.5 cm long... tiny!

I just returned from a weekend in Orillia ( 4436' 15" N - 79 25' 26" W), Ontario. We saw lots of Monarchs and found many eggs and tiny cats on the very young milkweed. It looks like it's going to be a great year!

Contributed by Don Davis

Just noticed the very first itty-bitty monarch caterpillar resting among the buds of one of our swamp milkweed plants this evening. I knew where to look because it had chewed a tiny hole in a leaf near the buds. It's only 4mm long and 1mm wide at this point but you can already see tiny stripes on its body and tiny "horns" at the head end of it. :)
Found Monarch Larva On Asclepias incarnata. None found yet on native Asclepias fascicularis. Have sighted Big female Monarch around for several weeks now. Hoping for more eggs/Larva soon.
The larva was on a milkweed plant in my garden. Today, 6/16/07, the J stage has begun.

One of my students brought a monarch caterpillar to school today.  He found it himself in a field near his house AS AN EGG!!!  He took it home and watched it crawl out of its egg and eat the case.  It's now a second instar and was munching actively at school today.  Another student has also found eggs near her home.  I wonder if this is unusually early for eastern Ontario.

Went to flower garden and saw 18 monarch caterpillars of different sizes.  went out to nursery to buy more milkweed plants so they would have food to eat.whatching to see where and when they J hook and form chrystalist. Brought it in and today, June 20th, it went into the "J" position, so tomorrow will be the start of "raising kids" for the summer.  There have been several monarch females, an older one and a fresh one flying around, but still have not found any eggs....my first sighting was May 30th, which is probably when the egg was layed for this caterpillar.  The swamp and common milkweed are in full bloom and much farther ahead by 2-3 weeks compared to other years.
Lots of eggs laid on 8 plants in yard by one monarch. Started to hatch today

While photographing Monarchs nectaring the milkweed in this incredible mountaintop wilderness in West Virginia, I also noticed small (first or second instar) Monarch caterpillars munching away on the leaves! These were the first I'd seen all year. I don't see them every year, so I was quite thrilled!

Found three(different stage)larvae eating on my tropical milk-weed. One was 5th instar, other two 3-4th instar.  Temp was dipping near 30 degrees so I brought them inside on the milkweed they were eating. Put them in clean aquarium with milkweed in water and left them to munch.  One pupated on a long branch, the other two continued to eat.  Weather warmed and I returned the crysalis and the two larvae outside back in the patch. We left town for several days and there's no sign of cats or crysalis.

I had four monarch caterpillars. Two have emerged(03/05/08) from chrysalis's, and 2 are remaining in the chrysalis. We have had 3 to five adult monarchs each day over 75 degrees for past 2 months (Jan & Feb 2008). I have a lot of milkweed and blooming plants to encourage their visits.

While we were planting one of the other garden beds the Kindergarteners and I found 3 tiny caterpillars on one of our milkweed plants.  They are about a half inch long and constantly eating.  I checked another one of our milkweed plants and found three more there.

We have had a few monarchs passing thru this week, but today the females I watched were "loading" the backyard curassavica with eggs. The one I watched closely for a long time was moderately faded, but a very, very faded monarch came into the garden for a few minutes. This second monarch, with its lack of color, was in great contrast and I am pretty certain it is a remigrant coming up out of Mexico. I got a few quick photos from late this afternoon (March 15) of what we call "loading" of the curassavica by the females.  There were some first instars, two that can be seen in one of the photos. It is hard to tell when our winter larvae stop and our larvae from remigrants start, but we figure this to be the week.  The center photo has 13 eggs. Some of the taller plants, at about 14", had as many as 42 eggs. http://www.asclepias.org/mar1508.html

I found 26 first and second instar monarch caterpillers on milkweeds, five miles north of Tallahassee, on Friday, 21 Mar 08. These are the first I have found this year. Richard RuBinoP.S.: Thirteen more today, Saturday, 22 Mar 08.

Milkweed has been almost nonexistant, but Friday Kay and I checked her lower pasture and found 34 small plants between 1" and 4.5" in height. Only a handful were the taller height. Most were ground-hugging 2" stubbies with few ramettes--3 or less.

Despite all that, we found 14 eggs and brought in 12 of those.

Saturday morning I checked milkweed in Shelby Park in downtown Eagle Pass: 7 plants no eggs.

Just now I noticed one tiny caterpillar and another beginning to eat its shell.

I've seen some adults back in the last couple of weeks, but today found at least a dozen larva in various stages of development on my plants (both Mexican and Swamp milkweed). A few small larvae are present on Asclepias viridis at Choctaw Trails in southwest Jackson as of March 31. Hatching likely occured earlier for some but these are the first observed at this site.

Here at Blackbeards Education we have well over 100 Monarch eggs on 12 milkweed plants.  Most of them emerged yesterday from the eggs.  They are still gray but beginning to show their stripes!
yesterday I found 4 larva on a butterfly plant in Mrs. Ryan's garden
Saw several very small Monarch Larva on several Bloodflower plants[Mexican Milkweed]

ON Airport Rd. in Rockwall we collected our larva and eggs for our class. The milkweed is very small and about .25% of what is was last year. We were able to collect about 20 on this one pasture but our usual other pastures have none. Not sure what it is about this one that made it plentiful.We were able to observe a female hunting for milkweed to lay her eggs. We had a great time.

On April 13, found 7 small larvae eating on butterfly plants (milkweed).  Checked today, April 14, found 5 on one plant (had completely devoured all the leaves), 3 on another plant, and 2 on another one.  2 very small larvae appeared dead.  Another was hanging from a leaf by a thread.

Wonderful sight! I saw our first monarch larva today, just born with his egg casement next to him (or her). I took some photos as best I could of the minute youngster. There were 8+ faded female monarchs egg-laying on this warm early afternoon of 78 degrees F. The males were nectaring on the wild garlic flowers and the blackberry blossoms -- the egg-laying females do not seem to take nectar breaks. I feel in awe of the inner spirit of these long-journeyed monarchs and very thankful to see them in this nursery habitat.

We have a bumper crop of caterpillars on our milkweed plants this spring.

Courtesy of Mike Quinn, Texas Department of Fish and Game

I got a call from someone in Round Rock (just north of Austin) with a report of an abundance of larvae. She said she lived there for13 years and had never seen the likes of it before...

Courtesy of Mike Quinn, Texas Department of Fish and Game

I have eggs. One caterpillar hatched this morning. I noticed the eggs Saturday afternoon. Some milkweed had sprouted in my lawn. And I fenced it off so I wouldn't step on it!! Who knows how long the eggs have been there. Can't be more than a few days. I saw probably 2 more monarchs flying around this weekend.

On April 13, 40-50 plants that son Richard, had grown over the winter in his greenhouse were moved outdoors and a faded, tattered female monarch found them and left many eggs. On April 22, many larvae were found.

We are purchasing more plants to feed this group of "babies" before school is out for the summer. Exciting!
I found my first tiny larva today on recently emerged tuberosa.  The larva looks to be no more than a couple of days old.  Leaf damage tipped me off.

This morning around 10:00 AM I found the first 4 larva out of the 7 eggs that I found in the Antelope Horn patch. One of them was just starting to hatch as I was checking on them. It was very special to see this for the first time. I'll be checking them every day to check their progress.
10 larva found, then became pupae
Saw the first monarch caterpillar - black head the size of a pinhead and almost transparent body.

I recovered 30 monarch larvae  (1st and 2nd instars) from my asclepius syriaca.  I'd  probably have  seen them sooner but we had had several days of rain and cool weather and I had not ventured out to the back.   I have still only seen one very faded monarch on April 23rd as she was laying these very eggs.
My milkweed patch at home has lots of baby monarchs.  There are up to 4 larvae on some of the plants.  They are very tiny.  We don't always see larvae in the spring here.  We hope it is a good year.

Yesterday I counted 19 tiny (1st instar) caterpillars on my common milkweed, swamp milkweed and butterfly weed!  I had reported finding many, many eggs (about 47, I think) 2 weeks ago and knew there would not be enough milkweed for them, because it was so early.  Well, the next day, the storms and rain started, and the temperature dropped to the 40's and nothing hatched over the next 9 days! I figured that there would be no little ones this go round! We then went out of town for a few days. Now, 2 weeks later from the 1st sighting, there are actually some survivors...and more milkweed, too!  I was not aware that eggs could sit that long and still be OK ! I will bring these inside to keep watch!

unbelievable-dug up some rooted plants 5/16/08 about a 20 minute ride from my home(to help feed 24 cats I received from Indiana)most of these cats are in the J position(5/20/08)-brought in the last of 12 sets of milkweed plants-surprise- first and second instar cats on the last three plants-I don't normally find cats until early July-well-so much for my note taking and Monarch predictions-looks like first adult,first egg and first larva all at once-go figure.

Found one larva in second instar on milkweed to the back of the property in the lightly wooded area - a bit sheltered from winds and etc...Also found the signs of larvae feeding on the same and nearby milkweed plants, but no larvae. We found 8 tiny Monarch larve on Wednesday.

I am truly amazed! I just found 7 monarch caterpillars that are about five days from hatching on the milkweed in my garden. Normally, I have NO monarch butterflies in my garden until August. Last year I had some at the end of July and the first eggs in August. Normally, they our butterflies are the ones that make the journey directly south to Mexico. The amazing thing is that I haven't seen any monarch butterflies yet. I have only seen one yellow swallowtail butterfly in my garden this year so far so to see a monarch so soon is IMPOSSIBLE. Isn't it?

First "baby" has emerged!

My lone egg hatched this morning! First larvae of the season. I bring the eggs in and raise them to release as butterflies each season.
Well, I missed the monarch butterflies, but found caterpillars about 1 cm long on our milkweed yesterday!  Yippee!
All three hatched

While weeding today we spotted a Monarch larva...3rd instar I think.We have lots of milkweed up now, A. Incarnata and A. Sryiaca...but the instar was not on them. It was found eating the tiniest of leaves on a seedling A. Incarnata that I raised from seed. The plant is only about an inch and a half high. Because I have a family of 5 baby bluebirds only a few feet from this garden, I brought the instar in fearing he might be served to one of them by foraging parents. After examining all the milkweed plants looking for eggs, I was surprised to fine only one egg. So I brought that in as well. Imagine...only one egg and one instar. Nothing more. How strange. And I have not seen a Monarch since the first week in May.

WI is having a classic slow Spring this year!  So pleasant!    Living Things are easier to observe at their awakenings this year than the past few springtimes in WI that were seriously abridged versions due to climate change. Seemed we hurtled from winter into hot, dry summer weather.  Flowers, birds, deer, butterflies, etc. seemed rushed into late summer behaviors and growth patterns.  There has been barely enough time to get out to observe the 'awakening times'.  Seemed native flowers just poked heads out only to mature and die back within a few short weeks. Fewer amphibians. I observed no night moths etc. MONARCH LARVAE have appeared in healthy numbers.  I started a count covering about 1/2 the area of this milkweed patch.  Today counted:  five eggs;  eight 1st Instar; eighteen 2nd Instar;  eleven 3rd Instar.  Not one sighting of an adult Monarch.  Many more swallowtail, Fritillary; and so many spring flowers growing in the wild.

WI has had heavy, heavy rainfalls.  Good for some things, such as the milkweed patch on top of a sandy hill!  And therefore Monarch larvae. Almost too many to count. All Instar phases present. Total numbers combined are in the 100's.   No chrysalides yet and a limited number of eggs left. Great spring!!!
