We have hosted over a dozen larva that are now in chrysalis!
My grandson and I found 6 larva!  Looking at the size of them, I would guess they are approximately 2 days old.
one monarch caterpillar, 5th instar, on stem near bottom of common milkweed plant in garden.   It appeared bright in color and plump/healthy looking.  It was resting quietly, not feeding about 7 PM

I was convinced I wouldn't see Monarch eggs for a couple more weeks! Especially since I'd seen only ONE Monarch so far this Spring. I was muttering to myself while bending over the new stalks of milkweed, being proactive this year,checking for pests and disease this year before the 'eggs are delivered'. When I spotted the familiar scalloped & fringed edges of a leaf and below this the unmistakeable teeny tiny specks of frass!    I rescued 12 healthy caterpillars and now that I have 'my' Monarchs to nurture and marvel at, I'm happily 'into' the 2009 Springtime.

i have reported finding eggs in last couple of days and now am happy to report that on the other side of the welland recreational canal i have found babies just hatched. i still have not seen any adult monarchs but of coarse there must be some since i found eggs and larvae.     it has been fairly cold and raining the last couple of days. the larvae i found were in a large patch of milkweed sheltered by a old railway bridge.     i also have seen a large number of yellow swallowtails which i have not seen for the nine years i have lived here. i did see the odd black swallowtail but never the yellow ones. thanks barb

We had a very cool beginning of May.  After awhile I didn't think the eggs were going to hatch but they finally did.  I started collecting the caterpillars to put into aquariums when they were about 1/2 inch long.  I collected 28 of them.

I found 18 monarch eggs on my common milkweed last Thursday (6-18-09).  All 18 eggs were put into rearing boxes and 8 of the eggs hatched this morning (6-21).  I saw my first female actually laying eggs about 2:00 p.m. today and found 4 more eggs.  Always a thrill to see the first Monarch of the season and see that first tiny caterpillar emerge from its shell!

I haven't actually seen one but one was here, I found my first cat today on my milkweed in my backyard. Guess I haven't been very observant, it is a 2nd instar already. It has been so cold and wet here, I am surprised to see it.

Courtesy of Monarch Watch

3 interstices on milkweed....first sightings of such... has been so unbearably hot here in northeast oklahoma that we can hardly get out (we're in our 70's)...but...they're hidding down in the leaves...will transplant to cages tomorrow..tachinids are the bad guys here.. philip g. .smithp.s. 102 degrees today..

I was weeding in our butterfly garden at our school and I saw a large caterpillar on the milkweed there.  It was a 5th instar I am sure.  I checked other plants, but didn't see any others.  As I was working, a female butterfly flew over to the milkweed.  I tried to be really still so I could see her lay some eggs, but she didn't stick around. It was a sunny still day.  That was my first for this year.
Eggs hatched. Have watched caterpillar grow to full size. Now waiting for them to spin their cocoon
Four caterpillars in various sizes on showy milkweed, Waters Creek Road.
Numerous larvae of varying sizes on milkweed in our garden!  Have only seen 2-3 adult monarchs.

I was encouraged when on my usual visit to the nearby wild milkweed patch, I discovered many, many monarch caterpillars eating happily on what promised to be a much healthier milkweed 'crop' this year than last.  I wasn't expecting any larvae because have not seen anymore Monarchs flying in the area since the first and only two spotted on Memorial Day. So I rescued twelve cats to raise in safety on my screened porch as always.  I returned the next evening to gather more before something or other destroyed or ate them and was looking forward to a summer like the one I enjoyed so much in 2007..hundreds of Monarchs raised & released!  I had just reached the crest of the hill, looked east to see the stand of milkweeds and ......there was not one milkweed to be seen.  I hoped I was dreaming but I wasn't.  My local Rod&Gun Club was having a shooting competition and wanted everything to 'look nice' so they mowed, copped up, every Monarch caterpillar, milkweed host and all of the prairie flow
Finally found several baby caterpillars and 4 eggs on mine and neighbor's milkweeds. Milkweeds are already about 4 ft.+ tall!
I found a 1st instar larva on Common Milkweed in my yard. It was near where I collected eggs a day earlier.
1st instar larva found on common milkweed in soybean field.
Discovered two Monarch caterpillars on milkweed plants in drainage ditch adjacent to house.  The first caterpillar was ~3 mm inlength, the second was ~10 mm in length.

I spotted my first monarch caterpillar yesterday, on 5 July 2009. It was hidden in the stems of the milkweed floral buds. I looked again for it this AM but could not find it but black grains of elimination were accumulating below those buds. The wind was blowing strongly yesterday making it hard to see and is still tossing the milkweed today. The tiny black and yellow caterpillar could easily disappear in the tighter bud stems. I expect there are others hidden as have found spots of black droppings on other plants.

The larva was feeding on a milkweed very close to where I saw an adult before. He seemed to be growing very large the two days i watched him. I wonder where he will make a chrysalis. Next time I will look for him since he is on a lone plant. Hopefully no one will disturb  him before I return to oour cabin.
Saw my first two tiny caterpillars today!!! about 2-3mm long, so tiny & cute!
Mature monarch caterpillar spotted on milkweed plant.
we have at least 10 larvae...one is lager than the rest. will keep an eye on them, they have a great home here.
Spotted first caterpillar, about 3 days old, on milkweed!
After being away for a couple of weeks, I returned home to find tiny holes in my milkweed plants and very tiny caterpillars....perhaps 12 to 15.
I was tending garden near my milkweed and I saw a monarch larva about an inch long on one of the leaves.

Monarch Larva was found on a milkweed plant in our school butterfly garden.  We have many milkweed as the host plants for the monarch and many nectar-rich perennial and annuals.  This was the first larva I had seen this season, but certainly do not work in the garden daily.  Have seen the adult butterflies in the garden and found several other larva today, July 21, 2009.

Looking out my bedroom window onto the Purple Coneflower/Milkweed Garden, I see ragged edges on a milkweed leaf.  I went outside to see ! Monarch Larva.  I found 3.  All were large.  Later, I could only find 2, so I'm hoping one went to pupate.  Actually, the "butterfly business" is begining to pick up.  In the last 2 days I've seen a Red Admiral, some Skippers, a horde of Pearl Cresent worms, 2 Monarchs, and a Question Mark.  One Painted Lady was at the Garden at the Zoo.
I have finally found five  monarch caterpillars on my swamp milkweed.  They are now, safe and dry,  inside separate containers and have fresh milkweed leaves.  The one is especially hungry.
We have two larvae, and one egg on a milkweed plant in our classroom.

I was thrilled to find "8" monarch caterpillars this evening..nestled in the blooms of the orange milkweed plant. I collected them and placed them on frest milkweed.  I plan to take them to my classroom for my 4th graders to observe and hopefully we will collect  enough to have a "Monarch Release" parade.
Nearly mature monarch larvae feeding on milkweed
found on milkweed in my yard
Hiwe have had a lot of butterfly traffic in the last several weeks. Today I found a monarch caterpillar along a queen caterpillar munching away on milkweed in my garden.

I have now gathered eight monarch caterpillars.  All but one, so far, has changed to the chrysalis.  I was fortunate to watch one change.  It amazes me everytime.  They are due to emerge between August 4 and the 6th.  Hopefully, all will go well.I have been rinsing off the milkweed leaves before putting them into the container.  The first thing that I look for, before rinsing, is an egg.  I find all sorts of other creatures and webs on the leaves.  I fear they may harm the caterpillars.
My kids found 6 caterpillars and I'm allowing them to feed and watch them until they're butterflies. I can't wait to see the look on their faces and to watch them fly away!
I found my first monarch caterpillar munching on milkweed in my garden today. It was on the same plant as a queen caterpillar. It has been a very dry, hot year.

we went for a Christmas walk to the Lake Merritt Garden center/ bird refuge first saw Monarch adult in flight then examined several milkweed stands ( physocarpa, curisavica)and found total of 11 larva in various stages of instar. the weather being very cold here and damp we retrieved the larva in order to raise them for release. we now have 6 hopefully viable chrysalids. three immediate deaths on first day, one chrysalis death.
Have quite a few Caterpillers, and lots of milkweed still even thu the cold snap..

I observed 3 monarch caterpillars feeding on my scarlet milkweed leaves AND buds(the only kind of milkweed I seem to be able to grow in sw FL). The smallest was about an inch, the other about an inch and a half, and the 3rd, about 2 inches. I guess I better check every day!
i have about twenty three caterpillar feeding on my twenty plants they are just about to chrysalize!!!  Can't wait to see them as adults

Stepped out into my backyard and found a Monarch caterpillar sitting in the sun on top of a waste basket turnined up side down. Hey, Guys, I found a Monarch larvae on Friday, 3/19/10, just hanging out on one of my dead Mexican Milkweed plants, and adjacent to my Fern Leaf Dill (which is growing like crazy, along with my broccoli, and cabbage). I brought him in and put him in my butterfly enclosure and am hoping for the best. I thought he was going into chyrsallis, but he still seems a little small, so I'll keep offering him milkweed. I just found two more Monarch larvae on my milkweed. One looks to be just hatched and other a few days old!

Spotted one tiny 1st instar larva where I saw a female monarch laying eggs on A. curassavica last week in the Herb Garden at the Desert Botanical Garden, Phoenix. Two other eggs look chewed on the side. Hope there is more viable ones that I missed. Sunny, 81 degrees, very light SW winds.

Altus and I went out and did a milkweed check in the backyard on A. curassavica just before the wind changed to the north.  Found 23 eggs, 1 egg hatching, and two first instars.  Don't see any rain coming, 77 dF, cloudy and humid.  Tomorrow we go seventy-five miles WNW to DeWitt County to check a pasture with a good coverage of A. asperula to check it for eggs and larvae.  Our daughter was there yesterday and said they saw six, maybe seven monarchs around and lots of asperula blooming.  We shall see ... if the weather holds.

Altus and I took three Monarch biologists with us to our pasture in NW DeWitt County, west of Cuero, about 75 eastof San Antonio, and in about four hours found several Monarch larvae and many eggs on Asclepias asperula that was abundant across the pasture.  In that time twenty-eight monarchs were netted to be observed, moderate fade to very, very faded, some tatter to very tattered with missing wing parts.  Another approx thirty were observed flying within twenty feet and another approx thirty flying at a greater distance.  At times the other four were pointing at different monarchs flying by as each observer yelled "Monarch!" ... I was the referee!  When we left the pasture before 4:00, I saw two monarchs at the gate and I got the "Don't Look!" look!  I think this is called remigration in South Central Texas on the best of days!

We found 3 caterpillars on the Cunningham Ranch at the south end of Quemado Valley in Maverick County. 1 first instar and 2 large second instar larvae were feeding on hierba de zizotes (A.oenotheroides) between 2-4" tall. Few fireants, but many spiders this spring.

With all the concern about the migration from MX, I am curious as to whether Monarch adults are being seen in Florida. Our state has suffered a very severe winter with freezing temperatures reaching far south into the peninsular interior.

My Waystation is #1777 in St. Petersburg, FL, about midway down the peninsula. Although I did discover about ten fifth instar larva over the past week on some sheltered A. curassavica, much of my planting was damaged by the cold, but not destroyed totally, I have not seen an adult flying since some time in February. By early April, normally monarchs are in numbers flying around, but nothing to date since February. As cold as it has been, I suspect these larva are probably from eggs laid in February. Larva have been growing very slowly, six weeks or longer and pupae two weeks or more to eclose.

Courtesy of Monarch Watch

Today I examined the milkweed plants (Asclepius viridis) in our pastures and was delighted to see quite a few monarch larva babies! The total number of plants looked at = 242.
Total eggs found = 33.

(Milkweed w/1 egg = 21, milkweed w/2 eggs = 6)

Total larva found = 22.
(Milkweed w/1 larva = 8, milkweed w/2 larva = 7)

There were 18 1st instars and 4 2nd instars, with most appearing to be newborn or around 1 day old. There were quite a few milkweed with the telltale chew hole of a new larva, but no larva seen. Some of the milkweed were already opening their blossoms (approximately 20). The day was overcast and 75 degrees F. I didn't see any monarch butterflies, but over the last week we have seen 2-4 each day nectaring, egg-laying, and flying.

This week Gibbs park has exploded with eggs and larve. We have seen up to 4 on a plant and each day they are growing bigger and bigger. The weather has been on the nasty side till today 04/07/10 and its hot and very windy. We are seeing more butterflies each day too. The Gibbs Park Monarch restoration program is almost finished and from now on in it will be maintenance and developing our educational program.

We have larval stage!

We probably have some 20 to 30, maybe more different milkweed plants. i have 100s of seedlings coming up now in pots too. there is larva everywhere

I found 12 larva on the 24th.  On the 25th I found 11 in just a small area.  I have found several every day and now have 36.  We raise and release them and last year released around 200.  We are off to a very good start this year.  We have never seen larva this early and to find so many is amazing.
Larva observed approximately 4 days after eggs sighted.  Feeding vigorously on milkweed leaf.  Now watching for evidence of 2nd instar stage.

Milkweed is more plentiful in my area than at this time last year. It is in bloom now with some beginning to produce seedpods. I have been checking two fields carefully for the past week for eggs and larvae. Until today I had not found any chewed leaves, larvae or eggs. Today I found one plant with a caterpillar about 2nd instar and a few chewed leaves. Considering that I have seen very few adult monarchs this spring I feel encouraged that this egg has survived predation, hopefully we will see more butterflies in our area when this generation has reaches the adult phase. The cautionary tale is that the fields I am monitoring are zoned for development. Human intervention is going to be vital to assure the availability of milkweed.

While checking milkweed a first instar monarch caterpillar was found.  The temperature was near 80 degrees and it was a sunny evening.  Can't wait to take it to school to share with my second grade class.

Greetings from the lovely Eastern Shore of Virginia!  Yesterday (Wed. June 23) I discovered 2 tiny monarch caterpillars on my common milkweed!  Yay!  A bit early this year, but we will take them when we get them!  Obviously, there has been a female monarch, but I didn't see it...but the evidence is here!  I have loads of milkweed here in our yard...including swamp, tropical, common and butterfly weed, (Waystation # 1361).  The common is about 8 feet tall, has bloomed beautifully, and it will soon be time to trim it back so new growth will be available for the late summer crowd!  I'll be nursing these 2 babies in this unbearable heat...hoping to to watch them grow to adulthood and new butterflies!

Here's an early June sighting: On June 8, hiking along the Lackawaxan River at Hawley PA, I checked the slightly chewed leaf of a young milkweed plant and found a 2nd instar monarch caterpillar. I bought it home, fed it, and this morning a female monarch hatched. On May 25, hiking the same area I'd observed and photographed two monarchs (both males), the earliest I'd seen adults in this decade.

They are either the victims of the heat, predators or jsut very good at hiding.

We've taken several caterpillars inside from milkweed plants we are growing to help promote growth.  Have 13 chryslsis now. This helps keep larve and 5th instar cats from preditors such as tacnid flies and birds, weather ect.

Lots of little cats found today - the female first seen 2 days ago was busier than I thought - not sure of numbers yet. the eggs I saw are now little catepillars. Growing bigger day by day.

I also see about six or so eggs . .  but could be more since I didn't look long and hard. Sighted 8 caterpillars about 1" long on Scarlett Milkweed.

Currently have about four caterpillars on the milkweed plants.  See some eggs too.  Did have over a dozen, but it has been cold and rainy and feel they did not survive Mother Nature.  They were small little tiny guys.

At the end of February, I posted a female laying eggs as my first observation of an adult in my location of St. Petersburg, FL, this spring though I had also recovered approximately seven larva which would indicate earlier visits.

I also noted that wasps were on the prowl for prey, but in spite of the wasps, which are this early in the season few in number, over the past two weeks I have recovered over 40 4th-5th instar monarch caterpillars from my milkweed planting. About half formed pupae to date and the remainder should in a day or two.

Adult sightings are more common now with one or two seen flying daily (3/13), almost all are females.

On Saturday,April 9, I took a break from sewing costumes to go outside and look at my milkweed, hoping that it was growing tall! The night before I found 48 eggs on about 12 less-than-3" tall milkweed plants. It was growing....several more plants had appeared; however, a faded female was searching the yard for plants. She had found the patch, but wanted more because she had lots of eggs to lay. She had to be satisfied with these plants and I watched as she returned again and again to lay more eggs. I couldn't count them all! She stayed all afternoon and covered the little plants with eggs...more than 100! Today (4/14) the first 10 hatchlings have appeared. Sunny days (70's) and cool nights(40's), very breezy. Severe weather expected for the weekend...

Several weeks ago, the monarchs came through and laid eggs.  I saved five in a "critter keeper" so that my 4th graders could witness every stage of a butterfly's life.  After the tiny cats were born, they fed them on tropical milkweed I had grown in my greenhouse.  Right on schedule, they all formed their chrysalides, and last Thursday and Friday, they emerged.  This was the first time this group of 4th graders had seen a butterfly emerge from its chrysalis.  I wish you could have heard their "ahhhhhhs" as it crawled out of the chrysalis.  It was inspiring!  So, we sent 5 Monarch adult males on their way to Canada.  It doesn't matter how many times I witness this event, it is still so exciting!!!

During the 7 days of warm, sunny temps last week, a female Monarch must have passed through and laid eggs on the milkweed that was 2-4 inches tall in my yard. A scan of smaller milkweed plants nearby, found 5. This is the earliest I have ever found hatched eggs. Have yet to see the butterfly, but they certainly have been here.
Yipee!!! Our eggs hatched yesterday!! I can't  wait till they become Monarchs!! Good thing we got them in before all this rain.

Well, I found the first cat of the season looking in the local cemetary milkweed patch, still munching his egg casing. All three in one day, Adult, egg and cat! The trifecta!!!(Do I win something? hehehe)

I reported this as an egg sighting for 6/1, but it hatched today, so I hope I'm doing the right thing by reporting it again as a larva sighting. It is happily munching milkweed in our kitchen.

I found 2 monarch eggs that soon produced 2 beautiful monarch caterpillars.  One of the caterpillars has already transformed into the gorgeous green chrysalis. I expect a monarch butterfly to be born in about 6-7 more days.
1st instar monarch larva on swamp milkweed plant at Etra Lake, East Windsor, NJ
Found a second instar.

Have sighted only 3 Monarchs so far this Spring.  Although few and far between they appear to be doing their best to perpetuate the species---have gathered 16 eggs and 11 1st and 2nd Instar caterpillars to raise them in a protected environment and release.

Just went for a walk through the field I usually get my monarchs in and found my first monarch caterpillar of the year. Haven’t seen a monarch butterfly yet, just several yellow swallowtails. Interestingly, one of the tornados went through the edge of that field and left some tree damage. The egg for this little guy must have been laid just about that time. Didn’t seem to bother him any! This is the earliest I have ever found caterpillars here.

Courtesy of Monarch Watch

Close inspection of "common" milkweeds outside showed 5 very tiny larvae.  Also, one hatched from egg brought inside less than 24 hours ago. Other eggs which were taken inside a short time ago are dark at the top (indicating larvae will emerge soon.)

We saw approximately 8 1-2 day old caterpillars munching on leaves in a cluster of 5 milkweed plants along the edge of the Thames River in Gibbons Park, London. It's the largest group of young caterpillars we've seen yet, and the majority of the sightings were made by my 3-year old son. He's got an eye for these little critters. Still haven't seen an adult monarch yet, though.

Three caterpillars hatched around the supper hour today from eggs brought in from outside on the Fifth of June.Looking at Milkweed patch there appears to be many eggs on young milkweeds.  Brought twenty-three eggs in today from plants the city will destroy when they cut the grass along the drainage ditch.Observed two monarch adults flying along drainage ditch...one was faded and the other was very bright (almost as though it was fresh from chrysalis.
I found an inch long larva on my very tall milkweed.  Very exciting.  Our weather is very hot so I hope that does not affect it.  The plant is in the shade.

I saw chewed leaves and frass on two small common milkweed plants. I would estimate the cats that produced it to be 4-5 days old. I did not however actually see the caterpillars. Hopefully they were hiding, but they could have been victims of predators, as tachnid wasps were present.
I found two newly hatched larva on small common milkweed plants.

Today, Friday, June 10, 2011, we found our first Monarch caterpillar nestled in a milkweed bud. This is extremely early in the season for our backyard garden. By the way, we have not seen any adult Monarchs yet.

We already have milkweed in the flowering stage-it happened so quickly. Was walking through a stand of milkweed and noticed some leaves all miky-looked more closely and sure enough there were two tiny caterpillars munching away!

comments: Found 5 monarch caterpillars this morning while weeding. We also found several eggs.

Small cats ALL OVER my Common Milkweed and Butterfly Weed.
Finally! Lots of swallowtail caterpillars but saw my first monarch caterpillar on the milkweed, which is just about to bloom.

I planted milkweed plants last year and watched many caterpillers change to a crysalis and then new butterflies. This year I have more milkweed plants and have not seen any butterflies. Low and behold,I have at least 15 caterpillers on my milkweed and still have not seen any Monarch butterflies. I do not know what to make of this! I would like to raise as many butterflies as possible.Last yearI did not have any crysalis until the end of summer,I am so excited!

Saw monarch flying through Lower Allen Park, near the Yellow Breeches Creek. Found 1 egg on Common milkweed (Asclepias Syriaca). Collected same, and caterpillar is about to molt to 3rd instar. (Also in First)

Saw the first Monarch on June 6th. There are many eggs now on my milkweed and they are now starting to hatch. The weather has been quite cool and wet, so have seen only one or two butterflies since then. Hoping this will be a good year.
Finally found the 1st monarch larva of the year today.  It was in the 1st instar stage.  I looked carefully at the nearby milkweed but did not find any more larva.

the deeper into the garden you go the more you will find today i foud 7!!!! but they are very small i almost missed a few.they all seem to be at the very top of the mild weed and i found none on the shorter plants only on the very tall one and there you have it my 7 caterpillar sightings

while walking along our dirt road i noticed some milkweed and was like what the heck ill just look to see if there are any little caterpillars i looked and found 2 more from my previouse 7 from the day befor in just a few hour our neibors mowed the ditches there for killing the caterpillars but...luckily i had taken them home to put in the milkwweed plants at the wayside in my yard :)>

Saturday (6/11)I found 11 eggs on my A. purpurasens and a 1st instar on common mw. Coordinates on LBI 39.43.19N/ 74.07.39W. There must have been a female monarch flitting through the area! 4 eggs have hatched as of Monday morning.

Courtesy of Monarch Watch
Found 2 caterpillers this morning, very light in color, perhaps a week old.  Have moved them to safety inside screened in patio.

Found four caterpillars feeding on milkweed while on an evening walk.  Two were 2nd instars, two were 4th instars.  Had not seen any eggs, and only one butterfly on one day so far this season in this area so was pleased to see the caterpillars.  Hopefully will see more soon.

Found chomping on top of a milkweed plant a larva that must be in instar 4 or 5. It was happily climbing around the tall milkweed and we snapped some pictures and were amazed by nature! It was a awesome night and he was out eating his dinner! We can download our pictures and send them over. It was beautiful! A great discovery. I was looking for monarch eggs and instar 1 or 2 and gasped at the site of this little fellow! We've enclosed our Father’s Day Monarch Egg hunt photos. Jensen's
In the garden, I found a Monarch laying her eggs while three cats emerged on another plant. Tiny little caterpillars...so exciting to see the first sign of the Monarch Journey.
I have counted 11 little ones in my garden. They are so precious and doing well. I was little worried with the cooler weather this past week, but all are doing fine this morning.Eating up a storm!
Sometime during the night a small larva came out of its egg on a milkweed leaf.

We have been checking the milkweed on our roadsides for the last week and finally found our first monarch larva.We found a first instar and a second instar.Two days later we, found 2 more first instar larvae.Two more days later, we found a 5th instar larva.
One of my students found 7 monarch larvae in her garden on saturday. My students are excited to watch them grow over the four days of school! Wishing my students a wonderful summer holiday.

First caterpillars observed on roadside speciosa milkweed slightly south of Somerset, Calif. Different ages of the caterpillars indicates at least two different females visited these roadside speciosa milkweed patches.
Nolan, 4 years old, found a 3rd or 4th instar caterpillar on a mint leaf next to a milkweed plant.

Found 10 larvae on my common Asclepias.  Never had them so early.  Cultured in my butterfly cage and released the 8 (2 males, 6 females) that emerged last week.  Vigorous animals, hope they will do well!
elarva was found feeding on milkweed on the banks of the Little Manistee river.

comments: I observed my first monarch larva that is about 1/2 inch long in my new monarch garden I created for Monarch Watch as a waystation. This is Waystation number 4357.

The variety of milkweed plants purchased at the spring monarchwatch.org spring sale are grown and flowering. Many of the plants sprouted from their seed kit are flowering, too. Haven't seen any Monarchs in my yard, however, yesterday I found a small larvae on one of the milkweeds. For a novice gardner, it's thrilling. Here's hoping there are many more!
4 caterpillars collected to raise. They were in a milkweed patch along the trailway.3 were instar 3s and one an instar 4. They are continuing to thrive!
Observed a couple chewed up milkweed plants and a first stage caterpillar about five miles south of Cadillac, MI along the White Pine bicycle trail.

We had two periods of egg-laying, both of which did not produce any caterpillars over 1/2" long.  All died.What will happen now is the Fall Migration will pass through and produce viable offspring, like the last three years. Those not migrating will die.It's not the heat, as the first batch died without the temp exceeding 85-deg F.

About a week after seeing the only Monarch of the season, I saw two cats on my Asclepias incarnata (Swamp Milkweed) which is planted right outside my front porch.  I only saw them for two days so I am hoping they survived and are tucked inside a chrysalis somewhere awaiting to emerge for their long journey to Mexico.  Oddly enough the only other Butterfly that I have seen this year was a Tiger Swallowtail in early spring and nothing since.

Within the past week, I am beginning to see monarch larva in my yard,(almost 4 acres including an acre we do not mow, with milkweed and flower growth encouraged) though I have only seen adults 3-4 times and only one at a time. I have planted butterfly weed, which is in it's 3rd year now, and have a pot of "Family Jewel" milkweed right by the front porch. I moved 3 caterpillars from this to a stand of wild (native) milkweed by the pond, so they would not consume the plant, but I watched one reach maturity there.(I was not able to find the chrysalis.)I also found one dead larva that appeared to have been attacked by an insect I call a "stink" or Shield Bug. I have never seen that before and I am not sure whether this insect kills/eats caterpillars or not. It seems that the caterpillars prefer the butterfly weed, or maybe the adults prefer the flowers, since they bloomed before the wild variety, which is coming into full bloom now.The tall butterfly bushes are coming into bloom now, so I expect to see more adults daily!

Numerous caterpillars on milkweed. On 06/25/11, chrysalis opened,now I have new caterpillars and chrysalis'. My milkweed plants are stripped bare. What will become of the new batch of butterflies that will come soon? I have no more milkweed plants.
saw 1/4 inch larva on milkweed in yard

On Friday evening I spotted 2 small Monarch larva. They hide close to the stems in the buds of the plants and are hard to find. We had been gone for a week, and with daily adult Monarch butterflies flitting about the last part of June and early July, I was hoping to see some results. But no larva was spotted until now. I Still have monarchs hovering about circling my plants.
It was a gift to see a monarch caterpillar in our milkweed patch with a group of children.  We brought it inside and the beautiful female emerged on July 9,2011!
Finally found my first larva of this year.  Have not seen many monarchs at all.  This larva was on swamp milkweed which was growing in my garden.  The plant was only about five inches high.

4 newly hatched caterpillars retrieved from swamp and tropical milkweed in my back yard today. Yippeeee!!!

Found all but 1 on Swamp Milkweed the other was on butterfly weed.

Among an estimated about 72 linear ft X est 3 ft wide, or 216 sq ft of Asclepias speciosa beside 395 just south of Gardnerville, one lonely larva.  Here are my notes:  "Plants extremely clean, few holes of other signs of chewing, except a few leaf-ends.  A red longhorn beetle appeared to be in process of chewing one such leaf.  No aphids.  Found one larva 4th or 5th instar.  (I took pictures of it). I was puzzled by the fact that there was no sign of chewing on any plant anywhere in the vicinity.  The only explanation I can come up with is that the larva is a survivor from one of those mowed plants.  Surely it couldn’t just be coming out of hibernation…….  Which was my first thought.  (It has been freezing at night until just recently)".  The mowed plants reference is to the fact that in that same place had also been, back in June when I inspected the area, A fascicularis.  Both species were reported then to be "about knee-high".  But when I came back, they had mowed along the drainage ditch and gotten all the A.fascicularis.

This larva was found way up in a small arroyo above Lake Topaz, the area is actually in Mono County, California.  If you contact me I can give you the exact coordinates. I have checked plants in this arroyo a few times since but have  never found monarch larvae.  (submission date is Feb 2012)

I never saw the Monarchs who left their eggs in my garden, but it has produced a bumper crop of healthy offspring.

I did not see an adult monarch; however, we collected eight first instar monarch caterpillars, two second instar monarch caterpillers, and two monarch eggs on our young milkweed plants.  My guess is that a female must have deposited eggs on the plants three to five days before the day we found the caterpillers and eggs (Friday, March 2nd).  This means the eggs were probably deposited during the last few days of February, much earlier than normal. We've collected first and second instars every day since that Friday--but we still haven't seen an adult.
larvae near milkweed in back yard

Nine lovely monarch larvae are eating my butterfly weed patch in the front yard.  I've had to place another smaller pot of butterfly weed inside the large pot because these 'babies' are eating up a storm and have a ways to go.  They're each about 1-1/2 inches long.  This is the pot from where another lovely butterfly recently emerged (previous report).  Then, while I was watching them, a beautiful monarch butterfly fluttered by!  No, it couldn't be Mommy!  Could it?  To be continued...

Today, sitting out reading in my backyard, I glanced over at a milkweed plant and noticed a very fat caterpillar munching away.  I expect in another day it will go off and form its chryssalis.

I had a chance today to check out the milkweed plants in our pasture. It is a beautiful sunny, breezy day starting out at about 70 degrees F and going up to about 85 degrees F. These are my results from about a half acre with spread out milkweed plants: 37 eggs, most with one egg per plant. 30 first instars, most being born today it seemed (one I witnessed), but some a bit larger and 4 were at 5mm length. This was a general survey, not comprehensive. During my outdoors activity looking for eggs and larva I also saw 7 monarchs flying low over the pasture at different times. Truly delighted to see the monarchs and their offspring!

While working in my yard, I saw three adult monarch butterflies. We have seven monarch caterpillars on our Mexican butterfly milkweed. Our milkweed has not lost leaves this winter and is already in full bloom.

I checked the fields at Choctaw Trails in SW Jackson, MS this afternoon and observed 6 females laying eggs on Asclepias viridis. I collected 48 eggs for distribution (and rearing) to elementary classes in the Clinton Public Schools. A few egg shells were also found and a single first instar larva was also present in the sample.

Since March 11, 2011, I have seen at least eight monarch butterflies emerge from their pupae.Based on my observations all these eight were females. There are at least five more pupae hanging about the outside of my house. I have also noticed monarch butterfly eggs and larvae on my milkweed plants. Last year I had plenty of monarch butterflies flying around my backyard.

I have about 10 or so milkweed plants in my yard. I have many, many caterpillars eating away, about 5 chrysalis that I have noticed, and a handful of monarchs that fly throughout the yard. I have given milkweed plants and seeds to neighbors. I have seen 2 dead monarchs today.

We have three chrysalis currently and about 15 caterpillars that have scaled the brick and other areas trying to find a spot to go to crysalis.  We have about another 15 - 20 caterpillars of all sizes on our milkweed.
Approx 26 Monarch caterpillars have completely stripped my large milkweed and several began moving away from it today, perhaps to pupate

We have been seeing Monarchs for the past 2 weeks.  I now have ist instar baby cats all over the milkweed.  This is early for our area here in Charleston, SC.  We all think it is because we really didn't have any winter weather.
noticed the first instar caterpillars today at the Louisiana Purchase Gardens & Zoo. we're working on a Monarch Waysation there :)

But seven made it to 3rd instar and I brought the pots inside to give them a better chance of surviving the birds and lizards!
Caterpillars have disappeared from a large plant which they finished stripping yesterday. All the leaves are also gone from a smaller plant, but the caterpillars continue to chew on the stems.

I noticed a few baby(1st instar) monarch caterpillars in a field of spider milkweed(asclepias viridis).

Already 7 large monarch caterpillars on my 3 milkweed plants. I will need to obtain more plants soon.

35 caterpillars left two of my milkweed plants during the past five days.  By 3/30 I had located 11 of them in various stages of forming into a chrysalis. Two of those died in the process. Five others-- all of which I saw complete the process - are now missing. Watching the whole cycle, beginning with seeing the female lay her eggs, has been exhilarating, an experience I'm sorry I've never had before.  And while I would have preferred to have done without the bitter reality that so few will ever become butterflies, I'm ready to plant more milkweed to get ready for the next cycle to begin.  Bit by bit I hope to make our garden a safer place for those generations to come.I'm grateful to this site for allowing us to share our experiences and to learn from others.
Tropical Milkweed loaded w/ 4th and (mostly) 5th instar larvae at Zilker Park in central Austin, TX.

Monarch enthusiast just reported having over 100 late instar monarch larvae on 6 tropical MW plants, two of which are (or what's left ofthem) taller than waist height. Plants overwintered here in Austin w/o freezing back.
We have 10 monarch FAT larva (caterpillars) on our 2 milkweed plants. One plant is completely eaten - they still have another. Assume they will go to chrysalis soon.

ON MARCH 30, 2012, WHILE WALKING IN OUR SCHOOL'S (JAMES BONHAM ACADEMY) SECRET GARDEN - A NATURAL WILDLIFE HABITAT - WE OBSERVED 10 MONARCH CATERPILLARS MOST OF THEM ABOUT ONE INCH AND A HALF LONG.  WE ARE WORRIED BECAUSE THEY ATE ALL OF THE MILKWEED PLANTS IN THIS PART OF THE GARDEN.  WHAT WILL HAPPEN NOW? - THE STUDENTS ARE WONDERING?

The milkweed has popped up everywhere in my area in the past 7 days - I have never seen so many eggs and larvae in all the years I have studied Monarchs in the field! The area that I have been observing is a new one to me (we recently moved) - we are high up on a hill just North of Comfort - there are several large, vacant lots (more like meadows) thick with wildflowers and swarming with all kinds of butterflies.  In the past two days, I have counted at least 100 eggs and have seen 25+ larvae which I believe to be about 1-2 days old. I am in heaven! Right before sunset this evening, I realized I have milkweed in my own front yard. In the last few minutes of daylight, I found 5 eggs and one freshly hatched larvae! I have taken several pictures and will send them from my computer soon (no luck sending from this iPhone!)

Looking at bluebonnets, found my first milkweed. Only about 6 inches tall, very sparse. Found two Monarch caterpillars, and possibly two more eggs. Monarchs came by last week, when milkweed wasn't out yet for the most part. So I'm happy I was able to get those two caterpillars for my second grade students to watch grow.
Monarch eggs are hatching!  3 of the initial 12 eggs brought in have hatched.  More are close.

Almost every small milkweed in my yard has at least 3 to 6 eggs or caterpillars on them!  Checked out 2 of my dependable showy mw patches for food and noticed one area the mw is just starting to emerge, and the other area had more advanced mw, but were covered with eggs and cats (1st-2nd instar) at least 6-8 per plant!  Off to look for more food!
Found milkweed with eggs on leaves. Found one very young monarch caterpillar.
Two larvae were found on a milkweed plant with about four eggs unhatched.

I discovered 10 cats this AM. They have totally eaten the 2 of the few milkweed that we had. Tomorrow AM we will be seeking milkweed at all local nurseries. Don't know how we missed seeing them before today.If necessary we may have to relocate a few to our friends garden.

Courtesy of TX-BUTTERFLY

A friend found eggs on Asclepias viridis growing on her property.  12 eggs were collected to be raised.  These eggs were shared with students at Roy Clark School in Tulsa.  Many of the eggs have hatched (as of April 3rd, 5 days later).
We are currently nursing around 40-50 caterpillars

Sighted a butterfly Tuesday crossing IH45 at Gladstell on our way home. Saw numerous ones flying about between here and Austin yesterday and came back home to 14 chrysalis and 8 j'd up caterpillars. Found one j'd guy on the floor, but put him on a fallen leaf last night and he was no where to be found this morning. Should have two dozen butterflies to release starting next weekend, if we don't give some of our batch of pupae to our Grandkids for Easter!

I have found an abundance of Monarch caterpillars in my backyard milkweed on South Padre.  However, the birds find them to be tasty food, so I try to raise them to adults in my cage in my home.  Such fun to release them as adults!
Observed at least 8 caterpillars feasting on 'antelope horn' plants. Picture has 3.

Monarchs have been sited for the last few weeks, seen them feeding and laying on my milkweeds but no eggs have hatched till today when I finally saw 2 first instars. Not sure why previous eggs have been unsuccessful as we have monarchs all year round.
A small 4th instar was found in my MLMP milkweed patch.  I believe that it is diseased.

In the MLMP@CNC milkweed patch (Cibolo Nature Center),78 A. asperula were found and contained 27 eggs, 5 first instars, and   3 third instars.  There were multiple monarchs on some plants: 3 eggs on same plant, 2 eggs on (other) same plant, 2 eggs AND 2 third instars on same plant, and 1 egg and 1 first instar on (other) same plant.

Lots of monarch eggs on the old and new milkweed plants. Several milkweed plants that are bearing new leaves have monarch eggs on them. There are also many eggs that have turned into caterpillars. The caterpillars are of different sizes ranging from a few millimeters to a few centimeters.
5 caterpillars

I first saw an adult on January 4th in Riverside. Jan. 12th another Monarch adult. 6 Monarch larvae on Swan plant 15th Jan. All at Riverside. I keep a diary. I was rearing Monarchs years ago so they keep coming back to our place.

I have been seeing Monarchs for some time this year.Here at our Riverside home found 8 large larvae yesterday (April 10) that had completely munched up several Asclepias plants. Fortunately found other plants in another part of the garden for them to continue munching on. Two adults flying around yesterday. It's hard to have enough food for them. Unfortunately my A. speciosa plants mature when adults are not in Riverside. However, at our home at Laguna Beach they use A. speciosa plants. Infact my A. speciosa plants in Riverside have just popped their heads above the soil so I have potted up some plants to take to LB.

Reported April 11

The eggs that were left are turning into caterpillars...some I brought in to protect and there are some on the plants....an egg is turning outside, so that was laid either May 1st or 2nd, so not too much extra time like last in the years for it to hatch, when they were here early. It was much colder and we had frost in the past. This year, they came after the bitter frost and the mulching helped protect the plants from the snow...they showed up a week later...good timing..going out with a friend and see if any more were laid along the road...thankfully the road spraying got delayed and they didn't spray...may try and gather up some more common milkweed....seems I don't have as much in the yard as usual...I know there was some kind of virus and I was digging out the bad ones and throwing them away...so maybe that is why we don't have as much...also the winter was much milder than usual, so maybe the seeds didn't get conditioned enough...

We implemented a Monarch Butterfly Habitat on 1/2 acre of city land in Shell Lake, in 2008. Five years later, after a good rainy season in 2011, the habitat has hundreds of common milkweed plants. There are hundreds of monarch eggs on milkweed (5/28). Last week (5/21)we started to see tiny emerged caterpillars. We will mark plants this week with tags attached to plant stakes. We purchased a Journey North butterfly house to monitor the life cycle of at least a few monarchs through their life cycle. Otherwise, we are educating the public when they come to visit the outdoor classroom. Washburn County was spared being sprayed by low flying planes. The gypsy moth is moving north. Surrounding counties are being sprayed. I am grateful that the rebounding monarchs at the habitat will be spared. After a 10 year decline in population, there appears to be a rebounding monarch population across the USA - east of the Rockies.

My way station #4551 is filled with nectar plants and host plants, an 8' x 8' x 8' butterfly house for protection of the caterpillars and eggs the Monarch lays.  Once she lays eggs I release her back into the open garden for her freedom.  I do not believe in keeping anything captive but at the same time I have to be concerned with protecting their next generation.  True butterfly gardening is hard work but worth every enjoyable second of it.  The rewards for your hard work and endless. I wish everybody could experience it but so many never take the time or interest to see the miracles happening in their own backyard or neighborhood.

I saw 10 caterpillars different sizes, No leaves on the milkweed but eating the stem.

I have so many larva that they have ate all my milkweed, it looks like sticks. (I have over 25 plants!) The larva are a varied instar stages. Still seeing Monarchs in the yard daily, many are mating. A lot of activity in the Galveston County area.

I have observed 10 larvae and three eggs.  I'm sure ther are more.  Many are in my classroom as they continue their life cycle.  I saw one monarch yesterday flying around the milkweed. This is the 1st Monarch butterfly I have seen in weeks in Austin.
last week (4/13), backyard butterfly bush loaded with all sizes of caterpillars.  (Count 8+).  Stripped 2/3 of plant over week.  Currently (4/20) do not see any larva.
Four small larvae and 3 more eggs were found at Choctaw Trails this morning during a follow-up rescue sponsored by the Clinton Nature Center.

I distinctly remember that when my yard guy came for the first time this year, March 24th, there were NO caterpillars to be seen. I failed to look for eggs, but there were obviously there, because, the next week there was an explosion of cats - probably 30. I would say. That date was likely March 31st.
I have 10-12 larvae on my milkweed. Can't wait to watch them everyday. I feel like a proud parent!!
Larva showing up on the milkweed.

We found the first larva of the season in out outdoor classroom today. We found about a dozen eating the tropical milkweed. We were really excited because we have seen very few adults so far this spring.
Large caterpillar, almost ready to pupate,but still eating on an asclepias asperula.
Saw two large Monarch Larva eating milkweed in my garden. Have not since any Monarch Butterflies.
Several caterpillars all at once - that was one busy mama Monarch.  Fortunately there is lots of milkweed available.

After seeing what I believe was a worn female flying around the garden I started checking my milkweed plants for eggs. Instead I found 2 caterpillars of about 2nd instar size. The following day I found another caterpillar of the same size that I missed the day before. The next day I found number 4 on the same plant. It couldn't have been more than a few days old. I'm so thankful that I just bought several more plants to add to the garden a few days before finding my children.
2nd instar caterpillar found in my garden today.
My sister who lives in Baton Rouge, found two 5th instar caterpillars on her tropical milkweed.
I checked a few milkweeds and found 3 larvae and 1 egg! They are going to school with me today.
First caterpillar. Looks 7 pr days old?

On April 18 on SoWestLep@yahoogroups.com> highly experience lepidopterist Ken Davenport reported: "Monarch (Danaus plexippus): Randall found three large larvae on a small milkweed plant at Ant Canyon and showed me these. I saw no adults."  Ant Canyon is location on the North Fork of the Kern River, about 11 miles north of the town of Kernville, California in the far southern Sierra Nevada mountains.
have seen the adult, but have some catapillars going into there cocoons not as many this year, but they are around.

We have discovered 3 medium sized larva and one that was much smaller.I took one to a protected area with tropical milkweed.  A day later he had hung himself and is preparing to form a chrysalis. ... Too early I suspect.  The other two had been attacked. I found the remains of one.  I have since taken the smallest to our indoor grow light with tropical milkweed in hopes of having at least one become a healthy monarch.  We are beginning to create new "native milkweed" gardens for next school year!
Then a cocoon formed on our porch
some monarchs with the milkweed my school has that I reported!
I never did see monarchs butterflies on my milkweed this spring but on Monday I found 2 caterpillars on my milkweed. I brought them in the house and this morning they are hanging in the "J" position.

We have several milkweed plants in our school playground areas.  It is a good thing we had several because there were so many caterpillars on one plant that the others were needed for feeding.  There were more than thirty caterpillars on the plant.  We were able to move about twenty into habitats according to size and are hoping for healthy butterflies for the children to enjoy.

My last of three eggs hatched today when i was at work but i can still take photos of him and anything i can find outside. He is an ivory color still, with a black head.Lots of cats moved indoors, but going out to explore tomorrow. I will send all the photos in one batch.

Monarch Waystation #299 at the Virginia Living Museum reports the first monarch larvae found in the Children's Learning Garden. Two young 2nd instar larvae [just "earned their stripes," it looks like!] were found on 2 separate common milkweeds that had spread outside the bed they were originally planted in.  They were both about 6-7 mm long.  I could only get one clear shot of one, the other dangled on a thread of silk and I couldn't get it in focus.

On May 20 I found 14 Monarch eggs and on May 21 I found another 10 eggs and one baby larva. All of this was great news because one or females laid eggs on the same plants as the day before, and the larva means that a female has been in the area for almost a week, give or take.
First larvae found at Cibolo Nature Center milkweed patch - 3 - 5th instars.
found around 8  larvas  , 2 sizes   aproximately  3 days old, an  hours old, because saw the egg next to some of the larvas  all of them in my milkweed
I have 3 1st instars here.
Larva sighting at Chesapeake Charter School. Young caterpillar just beginning to munch on our milkweed plants in the garden by the flagpole.

Counted 20 Monarch caterpillars on my milkweed plants! There was also a Monarch butterfly flying around in my garden that I watched for about 1/2 hour.  It was touching down on many flowering plants, mostly the milkweeds and drank some nectar.

I have 20 potted milkweed in bloom on my patio.  I found 9 caterpillars in second instar.   I have moved them all to one plant and they are thriving.  Must have had a visitor that I missed.  Have been seen the Monarchs flying around our area.  I might have more so have an eye out.  Too tiny for a photo but all thriving.
Just out of the egg today!
My first sighting of a female monarch was on Saturday 6/1. I found eggs and collected all of what I could find and today I have caterpillars hatching!  It is wonderful experience to raise Monarchs.

First sighting of Monarch Butterfly larva. Caterpillar had been on the milkweed then crawled away and spun onto the underside of a hibiscus bush. I just spotted it, but it looks like the butterfly should be emerging anytime soon.Also - we had about 15 eggs...but only 3 caterpillers. I think the wasps are the culprits?
I saved 18 eggs from being destroyed by the county road grater last night. Today, 3 have hatched and 2 more will hatch later today.

In a new patch of young milkweed, not observed in previous years, I found 6 newborn caterpillars, all the same size (probably 3 days old). 5 were each inside the tight new buds at the very tip of the 24 inch milkweed, one per plant (which probably protected them from predators). 1 was on a leaf.       Meanwhile, I have been checking many patches of local Frederick County VA milkweed since the end of April and this is the first sighting of anything related to monarchs. Usually, by this time of year, I have had chrysalises and emerged monarchs to show my students.  This is my 4th year raising monarchs.
I have found TWO big caterpillars on my Asclepias plants.

I have been raising Monarchs for about 9 years. This is the second latest date I have found evidence of Monarchs. Usually, I find several eggs or larva---this is the first year I have only found one larva.
Many caterpillars on our milkweed planted 3 weeks ago. The milkweed leaves are all gone. We purchased more plants so they can keep eating. One of the plants had a chrysalis attached.
1st instar found.  No adults seen yet.
First larva seen this season in the field. 5th instar feeding on milkweed stem.

This larva was found in milkweed sprouts, started from seed at our Veterinarian, Don Heimsoth's home in Cole Camp,Missouri. We have been late in all our planting.  We just hope and pray that this small one finds enough to substain him on through his transformation.
After looking at many, MANY common milkweed plants found ONE very small larva.  Perhaps only 2-3 days old?  In years past have sighted many more much sooner than this.
Just found this one eating away..looks like he's ready to turn here pretty quick, maybe even today :)

Found 8 catepillars just outside Twin Falls, Idaho. Attached is a picture of the little guys...I rescued them from a ditchbank before my Ag airplane swooped in to kill bugs in a pea field.  I grew up raising monarchs and have been dissapointed the last four years as they have not been around.  I am more than happy to report these as well as several adults in our area.
2nd instar larva as well as 4 eggs found on common milkweed on my property.  A friend and I had checked the general area yesterday but with no success.  Today was also my first sighting of an adult.

I did a thorough search of the milkweeds in my yard and found 3 second instar caterpillars, 2 on small common milkweed plants and 1 on swamp milkweed.  They were probably laid by the female I saw on June 12, the first and only monarch I've seen this year.
Have 10 caterpillars on my outdoor milkweed plants.

My wife noticed a little chew on one leaf in a large patch of milkweed by Lake Wazeecha. Turned out to be a newly hatched caterpillar. Further searches at the time and the next day found no other signs of eggs or chew activity. (Still waiting to see first adult.)
Found approx 4 day old caterpillar on a milkweed plant near Lake Somerset
In the ditch I spotted 2 milkweed plants that had a total of 5 caterpillars on them.  I brought them home and am enjoying watching them grow.

I haven't seen any butterflies or eggs but found my first monarch caterpillar on my milkweed today. The garden is certainly ready for them.  I brought it inside to raise. Otherwise they are attacked by predators.  The adult emerged on July 6th. I still have not seen a wild monarch although the one I raised is now wild and I hope it finds a mate.
i found my first cat today, its is probably 2 weeks old though.i have not seen the monarch butterfly yet but one must have been here a couple of weeks ago.
Usually find all my eggs/larva on upper leaves; however, all 5 first instar cats that I found were on leaves at the bottom of the milkweed.
Found a young 5th instar on swamp milkweed. Have been unable to find eggs or larvae, and then all of a sudden, a 5th instar!
On June 14,I counted 3 2nd instar cats on my common milkweed.  Today, June 28, there are 4 5th instar cats, but no new eggs.
I saw my 1st adult 15 day ago. This evening I found my first egg and larva. I've seen only 2 adults in the last week.
These are our first caterpillars this season.  Fat and happy.  Since our milkweed have been suffering a bit with the heat, they devoured most of it. :)
I have been checking our wild milkweed in my yard yearly since we moved to this house in 2004, and this is the first time I have found Monarch larva.
Only one Larva found so far this season.  Not a good sign.
We found a 3rd instar caterpillar on purple milkweed. It is now munching happily in a cage inside.
On a Common Milkweek plant in the Kippax Garden at Royal Botanical Gardens.
saw fist tiny larva yesterday
I now have a total of 10 cats that I am raising indoors. Hoping the total will soon pick up
4 early instar Monarch caterpillars discovered on common milkweed.
Had 12 larva hatch from eggs found on July 2nd.

Cat is in 5th instar. It was found in swamp milkweed and looks healthy. After further searching there was unfortunately no others found in any of our other milkweed plants. We transplanted him into a netted house we built to keep it safe and so we can watch the progress.
Found 2 1st instars on milkweed flowers.
It is a rainy, cool day.  But I ventured out to check on the Monarch egg laid on July 5th. Surprise...we have a baby!  Very tiny, almost too tiny to catch in a picture.
Spotted my first caterpillar this afternoon.Believe it to be a third instar.
First eggs found hatch out over night.
4 of the 8 eggs hatched today, the other 4 are getting ready!
My milkweed was inhabited with several caterpillars.  They seemed large, plump and very happy!

Found a larva hiding during the heat of the day and brought him in the house to my daughters  butterfly habitat.  By the time we came home from fireworks it was working on its chrysalis.  This morning we checked on it and the chrysalis...it was time.  Looked it up and found out it was a monarch.  It is still working on filling its wings.  We will let it go in a few hours.

I was cutting down some of my milkweed plants because they had gotten out of control.  I haven't seen a monarch of any kind all year.  I finished and when I looked inside the trash can there was a monarch caterpillar right on top of the pile.  I took it and put it on my other plants.

Yesterday 12 July, I found one caterpillar about an inch long on one of my milkweed.Later that day it had disappeared but this AM I spotted it on the same plant. Later at about noon, I could no longer find it. I have checked over all my plants but this is the only one I have found this season.
found 3 eggs now 2 eggs hatched now we have monarch cats the first for 2013

Found a lone first in-star caterpillar in our large milkweed bed.Removed an additional 100 plants that had finished blooming in hopes they will regenerate.  The 128 plants removed 3 weeks ago have sprouted and are now 1 1/2 feet tall.  Hoping that some monarchs will head our way this summer but it's not looking good at this point.

We have a milkweed patch not far from us where we have spotted only one to two monarchs at a time since July 11th. On July 11th we found two monarch caterpillars which we are currently raising as we are members of MonarchWatch.org. Unfortunately this milkweed field is teeming with tachnid flies, assassin bugs, wasps, and all the critters that can hurt monarch caterpillars as well so when we find caterpillars, we "snag" them. We had some sick andinfested caterpillars from this field last year...I wish monarchs could read so I could put up a sign that says "Monarchs!! Danger!!!Lay your eggs elsewhere!!" Today, July 15th we found two more caterpillars and saw a mating pair of monarchs!!! No eggs though....
I found a 2-inch monarch caterpillar eating on one of our milkweed plants.

Finally found two just hatched :) caterpillars on my swamp milkweed this past week.  Saw a butterfly couple months ago but someone snuck in and laid some eggs! Praying they make it. This is certainly the latest and the fewest of Monarchs I've seen in years!

Saw the first adult Monarch on July 7th, and it was a female. She obviously left some eggs! Found 6 tiny caterpillars on Butterfly Weed and on Common MW on July 15th. I brought them into a tent for rearing and will continue to look for more.
Observed one monarch caterpillar on my swamp milkweed. Fed there for 2 days. Formed chrysalis overnight on the second day. Hurray!
The egg I reported on July 4th has hatched.

I planted milkweed last year due to rabbits not liking it so much.  Went out to water the garden to water this evening and saw 2 huge caterpillars (2 inch long) and a few milkweed plants already had chrysalis (two).  My 9 year old told me they were Monarch. Doubled checked and confirmed.  Growing on a small patch of Dwarf Milkweed.
I observed two larva on Common Milkweed in a small garden located in a parking lot. They are the first two I have seen this year.
Four Monarch caterpillars were found in various sizes on our Milkweed and Swamp Milkweed.
noticed larvae on my milkweed.  Have a large bed of milkweed and saw about 9 larvae..so excited.
First two instars of the year.
Found 2 very tiny caterpillars in our backyard and 2 at my folk's property today. We were thrilled after not having any last year.
Just starting to see tiny Monarch larva on milkweed, but have not seen an actual Monarch butterfly.
Harvested 4 larvae that were approximately 2 days old from milkweed bed in order to raise into butterflies.
one lone larva on milkweed near a neighbor's home; VERY late sighting
found on milkweed in my garden; 2 eggs; VERY late first sighting
I found this little guy on the side of the road near Lakota school on country road 13.
So excited!  Found first egg today in the Irish Hills. Came home to find 4 more eggs, a first instar and a second instar in my own patch!  They are back!
Found my first monarch caterpillar on the milkweed growing in my pasture. Brought it inside to raise and release.
Just starting to see larva, but still haven't seen a adult Monarch.
Large larvae on narrow leaf milkweed.
found 4 monarch larva.  approx just hatched.

Our participants in our Monarch Butterfly Waystation Project have been combing our Native WI Prairie, a registered Waystation, for indications of Monarchs.  They have seen chew marks on leaves but no butterflies, eggs, or larvae until Devin, with keen eyes, spotted a larva on a Swamp Milkweed leaf.  It is probably a 1st instar.  The Swamp Milkweed plant was close to the pond's edge.  Other than about two sightings of a Monarch Butterfly, we have seen nothing else. Our neighborhood children that are taking part in this Waystation project are eager for more caterpillars.
First caterpillar noticed in Milkweed patch
Two larve found on milkweed.

After checking milkweed plants in my yard for a over a month, finally found my first sign of a monarch visit....two second instars on a four foot high milkweed plants in my front yard.  The milkweed has been flowering for weeks and is lush and green.  Lots of milkweed everywhere growing fast and tall with all the rain we have experienced this spring/summer but very few monarchs around to take advantage of such an excellent crop!

It turned out to be a somewhat disappointing summer for Monarch sightings. I reported seeing a few over six weeks ago. Those disappeared before I could get a photo. I saw a few more about a week later. They disappeared as well. I haven't seen another since. I walk with my dog for nearly two hours a day. If the Monarchs were here I would have a good chance of seeing them. No such luck but some were here long enough to lay eggs. I'm including a photo of a caterpillar we found on our walk yesterday.

Observed today (7/23/13) on Asclepias syriaca one 3rd and one 4th instar monarch larvae (two plants inspected, one on each).

found 1 caterpillar full grown on milkweed

I reported earlier a possible female at my butterfly milkweed.  I didn't notice any egg laying.  This morning was the first time in a few days i was able to look at my plants. Found one large caterpillar outside, brought it inside and now am waiting for butterfly to emerge. It made it through many 30 degree nights and frost.
Milkweed full of eggs, larvae as well as butterflies laying eggs and flying around constantly.

While covering our school gardens for a  potential frost, I discovered two very mature larvas on our milkweed.   I rescued them, and they completed their metamorphosis on 1/25.   I released them on 1/26 on a bright sunny day with temperatures in the 70's.

Gathering papers for the recycle bin and noticed a large Monarch caterpillar on the cement walk. I placed the caterpillar in a large glass jar with sprigs of butterfly bush and flowers. I raised five caterpillars to beautiful adult stage the same way in the Fall of 2011.
We have seen quite a few very small caterpillars on our milkweed plants.

I have seen two adults over the last two weeks.  I have only one milkweed plant but I would be willing to plant several more in my yard if I new where to get them.  I have seen three caterpillars on the plant this week.
maybe 6 larva and a few eggs.
I found three small monarch caterpillars in my yard today.

I actually have 2 gardens.  My home garden is in Santa Ana .At home I have had butterflies and cats all winter.  The weather has been very mild.  Today 2/3/14 I collected 14 caterpillars.  They are all sizes.  The weather is cooler today, for us = 60 degrees  I haven't seen any monarchs.  I have, however, found cabbage whites, gulf Frits , and sulphers flying throughout the garden.  Usually there are monarchs present too.  The garden is 21/2 yrs. old.My school garden also has monarch cats as well as the butterflies.  The school is located in Anaheim,  approx. 1/2 mile from Disneyland.  My home is about 10 miles east of the school.  The gardens are very similar in design, the school garden  has been remodeled recently,after 12 years. The  cats are still coming.  I have a group of 4th -6th graders that take care of this garden.  They are Garden Scholars

My wife and I were looking at our Aquatic Milkweed (Asclepias perennis) after we have had two hard freezes in January. Found one 2nd Instar and four 3rd Instars. Brought into the house to raise then release.

The first healthy Monarch caterpillars are hatching out fast with temps reaching 80f during some very humid work days here at the Live Monarch farm.  We have been preparing for the Monarch Migration by planting thousands of new milkweed. I am regularly enjoy viewing caterpillars on milkweed plants in my back yard.  successfully raised two caterpillars to butterflies this pass January, though I normally don't interfere with mother nature. Currently one caterpillar ready for chrysalis stage, other should be ready in two weeks

I bought milkweed plants not knowing that the plants were for monarch butterflies. fast forward since than I have been collecting my seeds from the milkweed and replanting the seeds. Altus and I have been watching monarchs all day.  We have observed a dozen close up between ten am and 3 pm, mostly faded females flying low and stopping on the native A. asperula plants in our pasture.   Altus went out a few minutes ago to check three plants in front of our RV and found a first instar on one of the A. asperula plants ... Kodak moment!  We drove to the new desert that is forming between San Antonio and Abilene the past three days, at they are thinking that!  They heard thunder Friday morning, nary a drop.  My brother has been staying in the pasture and counting monarchs and said the flow of monarchs held steady or increased a bit each day from five last Wednesday to eight they saw on Saturday.  This is still much better than last year but less than the years before that.  Our pasture is 65 miles ESE of San Antonio and 640 miles almost N of the sanctuaries.  We have been counting monarch flow thru the pasture for about fifteen years.

one larva -- 1st instar -- on milkweed

We haven't seen a monarch in about 10 days, but several immature milkweed plants in the garden now have caterpillars. This may cause a problem because the plants aren't large enough to sustain the caterpilars. Additional plants will need to be purchased and the caterpillars transferred.

This one is feeding from a yellow milkweed plant we just planted on our backyard last week!  About 1/2 inch in size.

One adult Monarch butterfly was gliding among the flowers around our buildings at the Clemson Insectary. One milkweed plant had eggs on it and one small caterpillar, which looked like Monarch eggs and Monarch 1st instar caterpillar.

Four Monarch caterpillars from small to large eating the leaves of a bush growing in my front yard. (The bush has red/yellow flowers in clusters, the sap is white). I didn't think they were vulnerable so I left them. They disappeared. In the year 2011 I succesfully tended five pupae which resulted in five, large beautiful Monarchs,.
Saw a 3rd and a 4th instar on A. asperula in my MLMP milkweed patch, Rocky Flats Too.  Eight days ago I had found 4 eggs.
Our eggs have hatched. We observed about 4-5 larva and some more eggs. Milkweed is growing strong! We should be OK and will keep you posted on progress!!!!

I just returned home from a week's trip and found 5 large monarch larvae on my milkweed plant. I bought 2 more from a local gardening nursery to make sure they all had enough food. Two of them have disappeared. I have made a mesh enclosure for the rest of them and two of the plants.  Two of the larvae have formed their chrysalises.  Today I found 3 more tiny larvae on the new plant in the enclosure. I hope these 6 can live to produce a few hundred more! I feel extremely good about being able to help the preservation and proliferation of this species!!
Se observaron 3 larvas de mariposa monarca en el Rio San Marcos en Cd. Victoria.

While working in the garden last weekend, a large larvae was spotted (and reported) on common milkweed.  He was put in a protective cage and is now in the chrysalis stage.  Also, what appeared to be a tiny egg was collected and it hatched yesterday.  Both are doing well.

Still waiting to see my 1st monarch!On Saturday (yesterday) I brought 15  eggs into the house to raise indoors. This morning I found 8 of the eggs had hatched. I guess you don't need to see one to raise them.

On Saturday my wife and I stopped along a dirt road to check some milkweed since we had seen a couple of monarch butterflies earlier in the day.  We found lots of eggs and new born caterpillars.  So, even though we are not seeing lots of monarchs, they are obviously passing through and laying eggs on milkweed.  Since it takes about 4 days for the egg to hatch, the eggs that had already hatched must have been deposited around the 25th or 27th.  This is a good sign for a comeback since last year was so poor.

I watched the first eggs being laid on the 23rd of May and knew I wasn't going to be able to see my first caterpillars hatch. I checked on the 27th and all were still eggs, we left on the 28th for our family trip to the Black Hills. I spotted my first caterpillar babies the night we got back home on the 1st of June. So happy to see a good handful of cats survived the 3" of much needed rain we received while we were away. I haven't done a head count yet but it looks like most of the 20 I saw as eggs are there. Hoping for a great Monarch year!

We have been anxiously watching our milkweed patches looking for signs of monarchs. Our kindergarten scientists discovered that while we somehow missed the eggs — and have not seen adult butterflies — we discovered our first larva. Monarchs have visited our milkweed!

On June 11   I found a 3 instar caterpillar in a milkweed blossom.  I then spent the rest of the day looking for another one among more than 75 common milkweed plants in my flower garden. Most are at least shoulder high and in full bloom.  I couldn't find a trace of one .

So happy to find that we have caterpillars on seven different a. tuberosa plants!  The female monarch who laid these eggs had a choice between big, blooming swamp milkweed, big, blooming tropical milkweed or the tiny and not then blooming native tuberosa!  Interesting choice and only those seven plants have one cat each!  Happy!

These were not tussock cats. They were big fat plump caterpillars with the classic monarch look. My daughter saw them as well and she took entomology as part of her agriculture ecology degree. They were having a lovely chow down on the swamp milkweed and the common milkweedThey were in the butterfly bee garden for the better part of a week and then no more. I was just out looking. Hard to find anything after two days of 70-80 k winds. My farm neighbour was spraying the field across the road from us. But that shouldn't have this kind of disappearing act. Ill also take a look to see if they are in their next stage.

My name is Charity, I am 8 yrs old. This summer my grandma and I are studying science. We found 2 colonies of Monarch larvae on two modest milk weed plants in our yard and are going to follow their progress. They look like what it calls 1st to 3rd instar stage. we think this is generation 2 and are hoping to follow them all summer til they migrate in sept or oct.

I have been out of town and crazy busy the past 2 weeks. I finally managed to carve out time to check my garden briefly on 6-27-14. I found a 5th instar on common milkweed near my mailbox. The next morning, I got up early and checked my yard. I searched nearly all the common milkweed and most of the swamp milkweed in my front yard; in 2 hours of searching, I found 2 more 5ths, and evidence of another 5th (frass, but no larva to be found), no eggs. I returned home later in the evening to find an adult monarch patrolling my yard, my first confirmed sighting this season. It was flying fast, skimming the tops of my milkweed and nectar plants, behaving like a territorial male (repeatedly circling the yard). But it never stopped long enough for me to get a good look and confirm if it was male or female.

I turned over about fifty leaves before I came across this monarch butterfly larva. Looks like the FIRST INSTAR. It looks like it just ate its egg shell in the last twenty-four hours. Luckily the egg is gone because tomorrow is Easter! The caterpillar has eaten a small area on the underside of the asclepias curassavica. There are an additional 26 plants nearby and about 20 more milkweed plants on the other side of the sidewalk. But this was the only and first caterpillar I have seen for 2015.I found an additional three eggs, two on this plant and one egg on the plant next to this one. The egg is reported in a separate observation. Weather was a cool 67º in San Antonio today but warms back up again tomorrow.You can see more photos that I shared on Instagram as user name @growmilkweed https://instagram.com/growmilkweedplants/

I unexpectedly found my first monarch caterpillar of the season today! Had been checking milkweed plants for eggs, but then this little baby turned up. In the photo he appears to be asking, "Are you done taking photos yet!" I found him around 2pm and am thinking he may have been hatched in early morning, as he is a first instar larva. I didn't find any other caterpillars this afternoon, but did find a lot of eggs and saw 3 faded monarchs laying eggs. I checked from about 1:30-2:30pm. It was a warm day (80 degrees F), partly cloudy with very gusty wind.

We have a flower garden and a small vegetable garden as well as a very large yard full of flowers and foliage. Mothers Day 2014 I received a Milkweed plant from my daughter. When it had seeds I planted them around our garden in hopes they would sprout. We've always had a large amount of butterflies, insects and wildlife but one exciting day early this year we found a Monarch chrysalis- what an amazing experience to watch hatch. From then on we have been on the lookout of more... May 4th I was gardening as usual but what I saw stopped me in my tracks thru out a small area there were Monarch caterpillars, all different sizes from tiny tiny to large. Since then there have been at least 8 I have found. One chrysalis we brought in hatched just yesterday, of course we let it go when it was ready to take flight. In hope it will stick around, we have a lots for it to enjoy. Fingers crossed they all will stay close or come back.
